1
00:01:32,926 --> 00:01:35,827
You mustn't listen
to what your younger brother says.

2
00:01:35,929 --> 00:01:39,023
I can't think of anyone less
an authority on female anatomy.

3
00:01:39,132 --> 00:01:41,032
He can see. It's enormous.

4
00:01:41,134 --> 00:01:44,934
- No, it isn't.
- It's hideous.

5
00:01:45,038 --> 00:01:48,007
Why don't you show me that dress again?

6
00:01:51,044 --> 00:01:54,013
It is a bit full here.
Let me have it.

7
00:01:56,416 --> 00:01:58,384
Thanks, Mom.

8
00:02:08,161 --> 00:02:10,129
Tsk.

9
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:45,097
<i>- Taxi.!
- Taxi. Taxi.!</i>

10
00:02:45,198 --> 00:02:46,859
<i>- Is this your cab?
- It's not my cab.</i>

11
00:02:46,966 --> 00:02:49,594
- Is this your cab?
- Really, it's not my cab.

12
00:02:49,702 --> 00:02:51,693
- We'll share it.
- But I don't want it.

13
00:02:51,804 --> 00:02:55,171
No, we'll share it. I insist.
That way there'll be no ill feelings.

14
00:02:55,275 --> 00:02:57,175
<i>- Are you going to Sally's too?
- No.</i>

15
00:02:57,277 --> 00:03:01,043
Well, that settles it. Come with us.
That way we'll all be going the same direction.

16
00:03:01,147 --> 00:03:03,615
You should come, otherwise
we're all gonna freeze out here.

17
00:03:03,716 --> 00:03:06,184
<i>Come on.!</i>

18
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,920
- Hi. I'm Nick.
- Hi, Nick. I'm Tom.

19
00:03:10,023 --> 00:03:11,923
- Nice to meet you.
- I'm Jane. This is Audrey.

20
00:03:12,025 --> 00:03:14,960
- Hi,Jane.
- You are going to Sally's, aren't you?

21
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:17,961
Of course there's a God.
We all basically know there is.

22
00:03:18,064 --> 00:03:20,464
<i>- I know no such thing.
- Of course you do.</i>

23
00:03:20,567 --> 00:03:24,435
When you think to yourself-And most of our
waking life is taken up thinking to ourself-

24
00:03:24,537 --> 00:03:27,700
<i>you must have that feeling
that your thoughts aren't entirely wasted...</i>

25
00:03:27,807 --> 00:03:29,707
<i>that, in some sense,
they are being heard.</i>

26
00:03:29,809 --> 00:03:32,801
Hey, I think it's this sensation
of silently being listened to...

27
00:03:32,912 --> 00:03:34,812
with total comprehension...

28
00:03:34,914 --> 00:03:37,314
- Hi, Sally.
- You got here so fast.

29
00:03:37,417 --> 00:03:40,113
- Hello!
- that represents our innate belief in a supreme being.

30
00:03:40,220 --> 00:03:42,120
- Nice to meet you.
- We stole his cab.

31
00:03:42,222 --> 00:03:45,123
- What's his name again?
- Tom Townsend.

32
00:03:45,225 --> 00:03:47,625
No, I think it was something else.

33
00:03:47,727 --> 00:03:50,218
No, it's Tom Townsend, I'm sure.

34
00:03:50,330 --> 00:03:52,230
He looks familiar.

35
00:03:52,332 --> 00:03:56,063
He's the guy that was sitting at the table
behind ours without talking to anyone all evening.

36
00:03:56,169 --> 00:03:59,070
Then, outside, he got the cab
that we were trying to flag down.

37
00:03:59,172 --> 00:04:02,073
But he insisted that we take it,
so Nick insisted that he come along too...

38
00:04:02,175 --> 00:04:04,075
so that there should be no ill feeling.

39
00:04:04,177 --> 00:04:07,305
What it shows is that a kind of belief
is innate in all of us.

40
00:04:07,413 --> 00:04:09,313
At some point
most of us lose that...

41
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:12,316
after which it can only be regained
by a conscious act of faith.

42
00:04:12,418 --> 00:04:14,318
You've experienced that?

43
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:16,320
Uh, no, I haven't.

44
00:04:16,422 --> 00:04:18,822
I- I hope to someday.

45
00:04:18,925 --> 00:04:22,190
Actually, it wasn't my cab. I was just there
waiting for the light to change when it pulled up.

46
00:04:22,295 --> 00:04:24,786
- I never take cabs.
- You never take cabs?

47
00:04:24,897 --> 00:04:27,297
No, I either walk
or take public transportation.

48
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:29,300
- Why?
- A lot of reasons.

49
00:04:29,402 --> 00:04:32,735
So you're one of those
public transportation snobs.

50
00:04:32,839 --> 00:04:36,297
- You look down on people who take taxis.
- No, not at all.

51
00:04:36,409 --> 00:04:40,641
<i>That's how New York's seen,
at least in the popular imagination.</i>

52
00:04:40,747 --> 00:04:43,648
I don't think that there is
a popular imagination.

53
00:04:43,750 --> 00:04:45,650
- What do you mean?
- Just that.

54
00:04:45,752 --> 00:04:48,721
I don't think that there is
a popular imagination.

55
00:04:48,821 --> 00:04:50,721
- Pomfret. Where did you go?
- Farmington.

56
00:04:50,823 --> 00:04:52,723
Both of us did.

57
00:04:52,825 --> 00:04:54,725
Did you know Serena Slocum there?

58
00:04:54,827 --> 00:04:56,727
- The inevitable question.
- What?

59
00:04:56,829 --> 00:05:01,232
All the guys ask that. Serena had
an incredible number of boyfriends. At least 20.

60
00:05:01,334 --> 00:05:04,235
She could manage it because
they were all at different schools...

61
00:05:04,337 --> 00:05:06,237
and she wrote letters
incredibly quickly.

62
00:05:06,339 --> 00:05:09,536
Three in a single study hall.
She became really famous.

63
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:12,805
<i>It's incredible how naive some guys are.
How do you know Serena?</i>

64
00:05:12,912 --> 00:05:15,813
<i>Actually, that might give someone
the wrong impression.</i>

65
00:05:15,915 --> 00:05:18,816
She wrote a lot of guys, but I'm sure
she liked some a lot more than others.

66
00:05:18,918 --> 00:05:22,251
Oh, you think so? I never noticed that.
How do you know Serena?

67
00:05:23,356 --> 00:05:25,221
I was one of her boyfriends.

68
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:28,226
Oh.
You must be Pomfret.

69
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:30,228
- Your letters were really good.
- Yes.

70
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:32,423
<i>- What do you mean?
- They were interesting.</i>

71
00:05:32,532 --> 00:05:34,659
Serena let you read my letters?

72
00:05:34,767 --> 00:05:36,325
No. She read them aloud.

73
00:05:37,670 --> 00:05:39,365
I can't believe it.

74
00:05:39,472 --> 00:05:41,872
She only read us the ones
that she thought were really good.

75
00:05:41,974 --> 00:05:43,874
Or really bad.
But yours were really good.

76
00:05:43,976 --> 00:05:47,275
There was no suggestion of ridicule, if that's
what's worrying you. At least not that I can recall.

77
00:05:47,380 --> 00:05:50,281
I remember a long letter you wrote Serena
about agrarian socialism.

78
00:05:50,383 --> 00:05:53,284
I think it was one of the first things
to set Alice Dreyer off about Marxism.

79
00:05:53,386 --> 00:05:55,946
Since then she's joined
the Red Underground Army.

80
00:05:56,055 --> 00:05:58,546
If she blows herself up,
it'll be your fault.

81
00:05:58,658 --> 00:06:01,559
<i>It's actually surprising
to see you at something like this.</i>

82
00:06:01,661 --> 00:06:04,391
In your letters, you expressed
a vehement opposition to deb parties...

83
00:06:04,497 --> 00:06:06,397
and to conventional society
in general.

84
00:06:06,499 --> 00:06:08,399
- I take it you've changed your mind.
- No.

85
00:06:08,501 --> 00:06:12,130
- I'm just as much opposed to them as ever.
- Then what made you decide to come tonight?

86
00:06:12,238 --> 00:06:13,865
He got an invitation.

87
00:06:13,973 --> 00:06:18,637
He's right. I got an invitation and didn't
particularly have anything else to do.

88
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:21,373
I think that's the case
with almost everybody.

89
00:06:21,481 --> 00:06:23,915
No. Nick goes
whether he's invited or not.

90
00:06:24,016 --> 00:06:28,476
Unlike Tom, I'm in favor of these kind of parties,
and I wanna show that support however I can.

91
00:06:28,588 --> 00:06:32,922
It's a bit ridiculous for someone to say
they're morally opposed to deb parties...

92
00:06:33,025 --> 00:06:34,925
and then attend them anyways.

93
00:06:35,027 --> 00:06:36,927
It's - It's untenable.

94
00:06:37,029 --> 00:06:39,395
- Everyone does.
- But that's no contradiction.

95
00:06:39,499 --> 00:06:41,399
I wasn't trying to.

96
00:06:41,501 --> 00:06:44,629
I think it's justifiable to go once,
to know firsthand what it is you oppose.

97
00:06:44,737 --> 00:06:47,638
I'd read Veblen, but it was amazing to see
that these things still go on.

98
00:06:47,740 --> 00:06:50,971
- You're a Marxist?
- No, I'm a committed socialist, not a Marxist.

99
00:06:51,077 --> 00:06:55,241
I favor the socialist model developed by
the 19th-century French social critic Fourier.

100
00:06:55,348 --> 00:06:57,077
You're a Fourierist?

101
00:06:57,183 --> 00:06:59,151
Yes.

102
00:06:59,252 --> 00:07:02,619
Fourierism was tried
in the 19th century and failed.

103
00:07:02,722 --> 00:07:05,054
I mean, wasn't Brook Farm Fourierist?

104
00:07:05,158 --> 00:07:07,490
- It failed.
- That's debatable.

105
00:07:07,593 --> 00:07:10,619
- Whether Brook Farm failed?
- That it ceased to exist, I'll grant you.

106
00:07:10,730 --> 00:07:13,722
But whether it was really a failure
I don't think can be definitively said.

107
00:07:13,833 --> 00:07:17,394
Well -Well, for me,
ceasing to exist is failure.

108
00:07:17,503 --> 00:07:20,131
I mean, that's -
that's pretty definitive.

109
00:07:20,239 --> 00:07:24,300
Well, everyone ceases to exist.
That doesn't mean everyone's a failure.

110
00:07:26,312 --> 00:07:28,542
- You really feel that way?
- I really do.

111
00:07:28,648 --> 00:07:30,946
- Really?
- Really!

112
00:07:31,050 --> 00:07:32,950
Tom Townsend.

113
00:07:33,052 --> 00:07:34,952
Tom Townsend.

114
00:07:35,054 --> 00:07:36,954
It's a fine name.

115
00:07:37,056 --> 00:07:39,684
What about Tommy?
Tommy Townsend?

116
00:07:39,792 --> 00:07:41,692
It's sounds more U.C.

117
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:43,694
Really? What's that?

118
00:07:43,796 --> 00:07:47,562
Well, we come here all the time,
thus the S.F.R.P. -

119
00:07:47,667 --> 00:07:50,067
- Sally Fowler Rat Pack.
- Oh.

120
00:07:51,103 --> 00:07:53,003
Mine and Charlie's are too.

121
00:07:53,105 --> 00:07:55,005
But that's the ex -
exception though.

122
00:07:55,107 --> 00:07:59,009
I mean, divorce is actually comparatively rare
among standard New York social types...

123
00:07:59,111 --> 00:08:01,011
contrary to what people might think.

124
00:08:01,113 --> 00:08:03,013
Well, usually there's
something wrong though.

125
00:08:03,115 --> 00:08:05,015
Dead fathers are a common problem.

126
00:08:05,117 --> 00:08:07,244
Jane's father's dead.
Very suddenly, last year.

127
00:08:07,353 --> 00:08:09,583
- Must have been awful for her.
- Yes.

128
00:08:09,689 --> 00:08:11,589
It was tough on him too.

129
00:08:11,691 --> 00:08:14,592
That's different though.
That doesn't mean a broken home.

130
00:08:14,694 --> 00:08:16,924
Well, it still means having your mother
go out on dates.

131
00:08:17,029 --> 00:08:20,430
My point was that the common image
of divorce and decadent behavior...

132
00:08:20,533 --> 00:08:22,933
being prevalent among
New York social types...

133
00:08:23,035 --> 00:08:24,935
is not really accurate.

134
00:08:25,037 --> 00:08:27,028
That's more Southampton.

135
00:08:39,719 --> 00:08:42,119
<i>Okay, Cynthia, let's cha-cha-cha.</i>

136
00:08:42,221 --> 00:08:44,121
It's completely ridiculous.

137
00:08:44,223 --> 00:08:46,623
Oh, now, the cha-cha
is no more ridiculous than life itself.

138
00:08:46,726 --> 00:08:49,217
- I don't know how to do it.
- You must have learned it in dancing school.

139
00:08:49,328 --> 00:08:51,421
<i>- Cynthia was a dancing school dropout.
- I've got it.</i>

140
00:08:51,531 --> 00:08:53,692
<i>? Cha-cha-cha?</i>

141
00:08:53,799 --> 00:08:55,630
Ah, the cha-cha.

142
00:08:55,735 --> 00:08:59,535
I don't think it's possible to forget the cha-cha.
I think you're blocking it out.

143
00:08:59,639 --> 00:09:03,439
# Cha-cha, cha-cha-cha
Cha-cha, cha-cha-cha #

144
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:05,374
# Cha-cha, cha-cha-cha #

145
00:09:05,478 --> 00:09:08,936
# Cha-cha, cha-cha-cha
Cha-cha, cha-cha-cha #

146
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:11,107
Tom! Audrey!
# Cha-cha-cha #

147
00:09:11,217 --> 00:09:14,118
<i>Tom! Audrey! # Cha-cha-cha #</i>

148
00:09:14,220 --> 00:09:16,154
<i>I love this.</i>

149
00:09:16,255 --> 00:09:18,155
<i>? Cha-cha-cha?</i>

150
00:09:18,257 --> 00:09:20,623
Oh!
# Cha-cha-cha #

151
00:09:20,726 --> 00:09:23,092
Bob! # Cha-cha-cha ##
Bob!

152
00:09:25,898 --> 00:09:27,866
- Hi.
- Hi.

153
00:09:29,235 --> 00:09:32,636
- What are you doing here in the dark?
- I was just getting a glass of water.

154
00:09:32,738 --> 00:09:34,706
Oh.

155
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:39,136
- It's gone awfully late.
- Yes.

156
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:41,145
What time do after-parties end?

157
00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:43,147
There's no set time.

158
00:09:43,249 --> 00:09:45,410
They usually end
whenever people go...

159
00:09:45,518 --> 00:09:48,009
or whenever the parents get up.

160
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:50,520
Although the last time I was here,
over Thanksgiving...

161
00:09:50,623 --> 00:09:52,853
Sally's parents asked us
to stay for breakfast.

162
00:09:52,959 --> 00:09:54,859
That's amazing.

163
00:09:54,961 --> 00:09:57,862
- No one stayed except Nick.
- Really?

164
00:09:57,964 --> 00:09:59,864
He likes everyone's parents.

165
00:09:59,966 --> 00:10:02,867
I don't think I've ever met
anyone's parents, except Serena's.

166
00:10:02,969 --> 00:10:05,938
I once had quite a long talk
with her father.

167
00:10:08,274 --> 00:10:10,765
What's the situation
between you and Serena now?

168
00:10:10,876 --> 00:10:12,844
There is none.

169
00:10:14,080 --> 00:10:17,049
- When did you stop seeing each other?
- Yale game weekend.

170
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:25,824
<i>Dawn in the big city.</i>

171
00:10:27,460 --> 00:10:29,928
There are eight million stories
out there.

172
00:10:42,675 --> 00:10:44,575
- Give our apologies to them.
- Oh, it's not necessary.

173
00:10:44,677 --> 00:10:46,577
No, I think it is.
Good night.

174
00:10:46,679 --> 00:10:48,579
- Good night.
- Good night, darling.

175
00:10:48,681 --> 00:10:50,581
- Good night.
- Thank you.

176
00:10:50,683 --> 00:10:52,583
- Oh, you're welcome.
- Thanks a lot.

177
00:10:52,685 --> 00:10:54,585
- You're welcome. We'll see you tonight?
- No.

178
00:10:54,687 --> 00:10:57,554
<i>- You should come. Hope's a friend of ours.
- You won't be coming to any more dances?</i>

179
00:10:57,657 --> 00:10:59,887
- No.
- Oh, well, that's a shame.

180
00:10:59,992 --> 00:11:02,552
- It was nice meeting you.
- Thank you. It was nice to meet you.

181
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:05,062
- Ciao, Sally. Ciao!
- Ciao!

182
00:11:05,164 --> 00:11:07,792
- Good luck with your Fourierism.
- Thank you.

183
00:11:11,837 --> 00:11:14,738
Unless we get a Checker,
we're gonna have to take two cabs.

184
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:17,741
- Don't worry about me. I'm gonna walk.
- Really? But it's terribly cold.

185
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:20,243
- I prefer to walk.
- You'll freeze dressed like that.

186
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:23,315
This is actually very warm.
It has a lining.

187
00:11:32,525 --> 00:11:34,789
- Good-bye. Ciao, Tom.
- Bye-bye, Tom.

188
00:11:34,894 --> 00:11:36,862
- Good night.
- Bye.

189
00:11:42,401 --> 00:11:44,301
Where are we headed?

190
00:11:44,403 --> 00:11:47,463
He's gonna freeze dressed like that
in weather like this.

191
00:11:47,573 --> 00:11:50,235
Driver, follow that pedestrian.

192
00:11:56,649 --> 00:11:59,812
- Hey, fella!
- We have a Checker. Can we give you a lift?

193
00:11:59,919 --> 00:12:01,910
- No, thanks.
- You sure?

194
00:12:02,021 --> 00:12:03,989
Yep. Thanks anyway.

195
00:12:14,066 --> 00:12:16,967
He's getting a crosstown bus.

196
00:12:17,069 --> 00:12:19,037
That explains it.

197
00:12:20,172 --> 00:12:22,140
A Westsider is amongst us.

198
00:13:15,161 --> 00:13:17,061
There is a real escort shortage.

199
00:13:17,163 --> 00:13:19,028
It's no joke.

200
00:13:19,131 --> 00:13:23,625
- What was your impression of him?
- He seemed nice. I didn't talk to him much.

201
00:13:23,736 --> 00:13:26,637
Mom, I don't want to seem rude.
I know I got up very late.

202
00:13:26,739 --> 00:13:28,639
But I'm having what,
for me, is breakfast...

203
00:13:28,741 --> 00:13:31,642
and I really don't want to think about
returning my tuxedo right now.

204
00:13:31,744 --> 00:13:34,645
- It's just that I think it's getting too late -
- Mom, get off my back!

205
00:13:34,747 --> 00:13:37,215
It's nearly 6:00.
They're going to close.

206
00:13:37,316 --> 00:13:38,943
Jesus!

207
00:13:42,655 --> 00:13:45,123
If I have to pay for another day-

208
00:14:12,318 --> 00:14:14,479
<i>Was it already closed?</i>

209
00:14:14,587 --> 00:14:16,953
<i>How much extra will it cost?</i>

210
00:14:17,056 --> 00:14:19,718
Twenty-five dollars.

211
00:14:19,825 --> 00:14:22,726
- I'm sorry about what I said earlier.
- Not at all.

212
00:14:22,828 --> 00:14:25,456
A girl called.
Her number's by the kitchen phone.

213
00:14:25,564 --> 00:14:27,794
<i>She said it was a bit urgent.</i>

214
00:14:27,900 --> 00:14:30,801
I know it's very late,
but we had trouble getting your number.

215
00:14:30,903 --> 00:14:34,566
Basically, we'd all be going together,
although officially you'd be Audrey's escort.

216
00:14:34,673 --> 00:14:36,607
- Who?
- Audrey Rouget.

217
00:14:36,709 --> 00:14:39,041
The party should be
of some sociological interest.

218
00:14:39,144 --> 00:14:42,011
Peter Duchin,
the Plaza ballroom, et cetera.

219
00:14:42,114 --> 00:14:44,947
- You think you'll be able to come?
- Um -

220
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:48,178
Well, actually, there's a bit
of an escort shortage.

221
00:15:17,850 --> 00:15:19,841
Hi, Rick.

222
00:15:19,952 --> 00:15:25,015
<i>What a mystery. Rick Von Sloneker
and Serena Slocum, still together.</i>

223
00:15:25,124 --> 00:15:27,615
<i>- Seems like months.
- It has been months.</i>

224
00:15:27,726 --> 00:15:30,126
Well, one thing's for certain -
she's lost her virginity by now.

225
00:15:30,229 --> 00:15:34,325
- How can you say that?
- You're right. Maybe she wasn't a virgin.

226
00:15:41,273 --> 00:15:44,174
- Riffraff.
- He's hardly that.

227
00:15:44,276 --> 00:15:47,439
Oh, you mean because of his title.
We're supposed to be impressed by that.

228
00:15:47,546 --> 00:15:51,277
On the contrary, I think the titled
aristocracy are the scum of the Earth.

229
00:15:54,219 --> 00:15:56,710
<i>By Tolstoy, War and Peace...</i>

230
00:15:56,822 --> 00:15:59,916
<i>and byJane Austen,
Persuasion and Mansfield Park.</i>

231
00:16:00,025 --> 00:16:02,653
<i>Mansfield Park?
You've got to be kidding.</i>

232
00:16:02,761 --> 00:16:05,457
- No.
- But it's a notoriously bad book.

233
00:16:05,564 --> 00:16:07,964
Even Lionel Trilling,
one of her greatest admirers, thought that.

234
00:16:08,067 --> 00:16:10,661
Well, if Lionel Trilling thought that,
he's an idiot.

235
00:16:10,769 --> 00:16:13,966
The whole story
revolves around, what...

236
00:16:14,073 --> 00:16:16,473
<i>the immorality of a group of young people
putting on a play.</i>

237
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:19,510
In the context of the novel
it makes perfect sense.

238
00:16:19,611 --> 00:16:22,512
But the context of the novel,
and nearly everything Jane Austen wrote...

239
00:16:22,614 --> 00:16:24,514
is near ridiculous
from today's perspective.

240
00:16:24,616 --> 00:16:27,608
Has it ever occurred to you that today,
looked at from Jane Austen's perspective...

241
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:29,688
would look even worse?

242
00:16:36,729 --> 00:16:38,629
You must be freezing
dressed in that.

243
00:16:38,731 --> 00:16:42,030
- It has a lining.
- What kind of lining is it?

244
00:16:42,134 --> 00:16:44,034
You gonna wear a raincoat all winter?

245
00:16:44,136 --> 00:16:46,900
Princeton's south of here.
I guess it's a lot warmer.

246
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,907
No, I just didn't know
where to get a good overcoat.

247
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:52,409
Uh, Brooks,J. Press, Tripler-

248
00:16:52,511 --> 00:16:54,911
Actually, I haven't had time to buy one.

249
00:17:16,835 --> 00:17:20,271
<i>I'm not sure I wanna go back to Princeton
next year. It's too much of a country club for me.</i>

250
00:17:20,372 --> 00:17:22,272
You really shouldn't
treat Serena that way.

251
00:17:22,374 --> 00:17:24,934
- What?
- Giving her the silent treatment.

252
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:27,945
- I'm not giving her the silent treatment.
- Come on.

253
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:30,948
I'm not giving her the silent treatment.
I just don't have anything to say to her.

254
00:17:31,050 --> 00:17:33,951
Listen, I know you're angry with her.
You're probably right to be.

255
00:17:34,053 --> 00:17:37,454
But it's still not right to treat her that way.
I think Serena really feels hurt by it.

256
00:17:37,556 --> 00:17:39,456
Oh, give me a break!

257
00:17:39,558 --> 00:17:41,788
Serena Slocum, a real feeling?

258
00:17:41,894 --> 00:17:44,795
Serena's basically a good person.

259
00:17:44,897 --> 00:17:48,424
- She has feelings like anybody else.
- I find that very hard to believe.

260
00:17:48,534 --> 00:17:50,968
All this is - is pretty deceptive.

261
00:17:51,070 --> 00:17:53,971
- All what?
- Well, I -

262
00:17:54,073 --> 00:17:57,804
I think that - that -
that we are all, in a sense, doomed.

263
00:17:57,910 --> 00:17:59,775
What are you talking about?

264
00:17:59,878 --> 00:18:01,778
Downward social mobility.

265
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:04,781
We hear a lot about
the great social mobility in America...

266
00:18:04,883 --> 00:18:08,546
with the focus usually on
the comparative ease of moving upwards.

267
00:18:08,654 --> 00:18:12,522
What's less discussed is
how easy it is to - to go down.

268
00:18:12,624 --> 00:18:15,525
I think that's the -
the direction that we're all heading in.

269
00:18:15,627 --> 00:18:18,528
And I think that the downward fall
is gonna be very fast.

270
00:18:18,630 --> 00:18:23,124
Not just for us as individuals,
but the whole preppy class.

271
00:18:23,235 --> 00:18:25,635
Where do you get all this?

272
00:18:25,737 --> 00:18:29,833
Well,just look around. Take those
of our fathers who grew up very well off.

273
00:18:29,942 --> 00:18:32,536
<i>Maybe their careers
started out well enough...</i>

274
00:18:32,644 --> 00:18:35,772
<i>butjust as their contemporaries
really began to accomplish things...</i>

275
00:18:35,881 --> 00:18:37,849
<i>they started to quit...</i>

276
00:18:37,950 --> 00:18:39,850
on rising above office politics...

277
00:18:39,952 --> 00:18:42,853
or- or refusing to compete
and risk open failure.

278
00:18:42,955 --> 00:18:45,515
Or not - not doing
the humdrum part of the job.

279
00:18:45,624 --> 00:18:47,524
<i>Or only doing the humdrum part.</i>

280
00:18:47,626 --> 00:18:51,756
Or gradually spending more and more time
on something more interesting -

281
00:18:51,864 --> 00:18:53,764
um, conservation, or the arts...

282
00:18:53,866 --> 00:18:56,198
where even if they were total failures
no one would know it.

283
00:18:56,301 --> 00:18:58,360
Okay.

284
00:18:58,470 --> 00:19:01,371
I guess we all know
who you're talking about.

285
00:19:01,473 --> 00:19:03,441
I can't deny your point, but...

286
00:19:03,542 --> 00:19:07,171
unlike you, I've always
assumed I'd be a failure anyway.

287
00:19:07,279 --> 00:19:10,305
That's why I plan to marry
an extremely rich woman.

288
00:19:11,350 --> 00:19:13,250
Pretty depressing.

289
00:19:13,352 --> 00:19:15,912
A bit overstated, don't you think?

290
00:19:16,021 --> 00:19:18,922
- I'm not so sure.
- "Doomed. "

291
00:19:19,024 --> 00:19:20,924
Even if he were right...

292
00:19:21,026 --> 00:19:24,189
it wouldn't be any great tragedy if some
of these people lost their class prerogatives.

293
00:19:24,296 --> 00:19:26,696
"These people" are everyone I know.

294
00:19:26,798 --> 00:19:31,758
And besides, it's not a question of losing
class prerogatives, whatever that means...

295
00:19:31,870 --> 00:19:34,771
but the prospect of wasting
your whole productive life...

296
00:19:34,873 --> 00:19:36,773
of personal failure.

297
00:19:36,875 --> 00:19:38,775
That's so melodramatic.

298
00:19:38,877 --> 00:19:41,778
Life is melodramatic,
if you look at the whole sweep of it.

299
00:19:41,880 --> 00:19:44,280
I don't know.

300
00:19:44,383 --> 00:19:47,284
I think my father
considers himself a failure...

301
00:19:47,386 --> 00:19:49,354
although I don't think he's one.

302
00:19:50,656 --> 00:19:52,954
I guess few people's lives...

303
00:19:53,058 --> 00:19:55,026
match their own expectations.

304
00:20:00,966 --> 00:20:03,867
I always drink two glasses of water
before going to bed anyway.

305
00:20:03,969 --> 00:20:05,937
It's great for your complexion.

306
00:20:06,104 --> 00:20:10,939
I thought I should mention I'm putting you
on the floor committee for the Christmas ball.

307
00:20:11,043 --> 00:20:14,638
Essentially, all it means is, you'll be able to go
on your own rather than as someone's escort...

308
00:20:14,746 --> 00:20:17,647
and that you'll get
a white carnation for your lapel.

309
00:20:17,749 --> 00:20:20,650
Thanks a lot, but actually I'm not
planning to go to any more dances.

310
00:20:20,752 --> 00:20:22,652
You weren't?

311
00:20:22,754 --> 00:20:25,154
Well, I strongly advise you
to change your mind.

312
00:20:25,257 --> 00:20:27,555
Is it that your resources
are limited?

313
00:20:27,659 --> 00:20:30,924
This is about the only economical
social life you're gonna find in New York.

314
00:20:31,029 --> 00:20:34,931
Music, drinks, entertainment,
hot, nutritious meals...

315
00:20:35,033 --> 00:20:37,228
all at no expense to you.

316
00:20:37,336 --> 00:20:40,237
Basically, all you need
is one suit of evening clothes...

317
00:20:40,339 --> 00:20:42,239
and a tailcoat.

318
00:20:42,341 --> 00:20:46,243
Dances are either white tie or black tie,
so you only need two ties.

319
00:20:47,279 --> 00:20:49,679
- You rented that from where?
- A.T. Harris.

320
00:20:49,781 --> 00:20:52,011
Oh, good!
You know about Harris.

321
00:20:52,117 --> 00:20:54,483
They also sell them secondhand,
very inexpensively.

322
00:20:54,586 --> 00:20:56,486
<i>- It's a good arrangement.
- Thanks a lot.</i>

323
00:20:56,588 --> 00:20:59,148
My resources are limited,
but actually that's not it.

324
00:20:59,258 --> 00:21:02,750
<i>I know. You're opposed
to these parties on principle.</i>

325
00:21:02,861 --> 00:21:05,261
- Yes.
- Exactly what principle is that?

326
00:21:05,364 --> 00:21:07,264
Well -

327
00:21:07,366 --> 00:21:10,267
The principle that one shouldn't be out
at night eating hors d'oeuvres...

328
00:21:10,369 --> 00:21:13,270
when one could be home
worrying about the less fortunate.

329
00:21:13,372 --> 00:21:15,272
Pretty much, yes.

330
00:21:15,374 --> 00:21:19,367
<i>Has it ever occurred to you
that you are the less fortunate?</i>

331
00:21:20,412 --> 00:21:23,472
I mean, there's something
a tiny bit arrogant...

332
00:21:23,582 --> 00:21:28,315
about people going around feeling sorry
for other people they consider less fortunate.

333
00:21:28,420 --> 00:21:31,116
<i>Are the more fortunate
really so terrific?</i>

334
00:21:31,223 --> 00:21:33,783
Do you want some much-richer guy
going around saying...

335
00:21:33,892 --> 00:21:38,386
"Poor Tom Townsend doesn't even have
a winter jacket - I can't go to any more parties"?

336
00:21:38,497 --> 00:21:40,397
That's a bit cynical.

337
00:21:40,499 --> 00:21:43,400
This is not just a matter
of what you personally prefer.

338
00:21:43,502 --> 00:21:46,699
I'll tell you this in confidence.
You've made a big impression on these girls -

339
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:48,705
<i>- Oh, come on.!
- No, I'm serious.</i>

340
00:21:48,807 --> 00:21:53,210
They like you and are now
counting on you as an escort.

341
00:21:53,312 --> 00:21:55,678
Well, I like them, too,
but that doesn't -

342
00:21:55,781 --> 00:21:59,683
<i>I'm not sure if you realize this, but these girls
are at a very vulnerable point in their lives.</i>

343
00:21:59,785 --> 00:22:04,779
All of this is much more emotional
and difficult for them than it is for us.

344
00:22:04,890 --> 00:22:06,790
They're on display.

345
00:22:06,892 --> 00:22:10,157
They have to call the guys up
and invite them as escorts.

346
00:22:10,262 --> 00:22:13,163
And preppy girls mature socially
much later than others do.

347
00:22:13,265 --> 00:22:16,166
For many of them, this is the first
serious social life they've had...

348
00:22:16,268 --> 00:22:20,398
and if you just disappear now,
they're gonna take that as personal rejection.

349
00:22:20,505 --> 00:22:23,668
- Give me a break.
- I'm not entirely joking.

350
00:22:23,775 --> 00:22:25,834
You should go.

351
00:22:25,944 --> 00:22:29,436
IfThorstein Veblen were here,
he'd tell you the same thing.

352
00:22:32,351 --> 00:22:35,252
I'll meet you at 4:30 at Brooks,
main floor, southwest corner...

353
00:22:35,354 --> 00:22:37,879
where the pajamas intersect
with the expensive shirts...

354
00:22:37,989 --> 00:22:39,957
right across from
the undershorts counter.

355
00:22:42,094 --> 00:22:44,460
As a romance,
it never really existed.

356
00:22:44,563 --> 00:22:47,054
- Really?
- I made a classic mistake.

357
00:22:47,165 --> 00:22:49,633
I fell in love with Serena
long before I met her.

358
00:22:49,735 --> 00:22:53,068
I'd seen her at a Chapin dance,
but I didn't really meet her until a year later.

359
00:22:53,171 --> 00:22:58,074
Even before we started going out,
I'd built up this huge romantic vision about her.

360
00:22:58,176 --> 00:23:00,076
It should be just the reverse.

361
00:23:00,178 --> 00:23:02,578
You should get to know someone
gradually, over time...

362
00:23:02,681 --> 00:23:05,081
before the possibility of falling in love
even occurs to you.

363
00:23:05,183 --> 00:23:07,083
Possibly not even then.

364
00:23:07,185 --> 00:23:09,346
So the experience
has somewhat hardened you?

365
00:23:09,454 --> 00:23:14,153
Yes. At least, it's a very bad idea to fall
for someone who doesn't for you.

366
00:23:15,961 --> 00:23:19,863
Yes, but you can't know that you'll feel
exactly the same way all the time.

367
00:23:19,965 --> 00:23:22,866
I mean, I suppose
there will be risk in any romance.

368
00:23:22,968 --> 00:23:24,868
I suppose so.

369
00:23:24,970 --> 00:23:27,438
Well, this is my building.

370
00:23:28,473 --> 00:23:30,839
- Thanks very much for coming.
- Thank you.

371
00:23:32,811 --> 00:23:35,507
You'll come again tomorrow?
It'll be as a group.

372
00:23:35,614 --> 00:23:37,582
Yes.

373
00:24:10,849 --> 00:24:13,249
Thanks, Mom.
I know how tight things have been.

374
00:24:13,351 --> 00:24:16,013
<i>- Things haven't been that tight.
- I'll pay you back next month.</i>

375
00:24:16,121 --> 00:24:18,021
Or in February.

376
00:24:18,123 --> 00:24:21,024
- Has Dad called?
- He's never called here. You know that.

377
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:23,720
- I thought maybe his office had.
- No.

378
00:24:23,829 --> 00:24:25,797
Thanks a lot.

379
00:24:30,602 --> 00:24:33,264
- They're normally this long in the back?
- Yes, sir.

380
00:24:33,371 --> 00:24:35,669
- Uh-huh.
- Like to try on the tuxedo?

381
00:24:35,774 --> 00:24:37,742
Okay.

382
00:24:38,977 --> 00:24:40,877
Here you go.

383
00:24:43,748 --> 00:24:45,648
I think I'd prefer one
more like the one I rented.

384
00:24:45,750 --> 00:24:48,514
<i>- That is the one you rented.
- Oh.</i>

385
00:24:48,620 --> 00:24:51,612
I didn't realize it looked like this.
I guess it'll be all right.

386
00:24:51,723 --> 00:24:53,691
Thank you.

387
00:24:57,195 --> 00:25:00,164
You haven't seen this?
Detachable collar.

388
00:25:00,265 --> 00:25:03,723
Not many people wear them anymore.
They look much better.

389
00:25:03,835 --> 00:25:07,737
So many things which were better in the past
have been abandoned for supposed convenience.

390
00:25:07,839 --> 00:25:12,435
- I had no idea anyone wore those anymore.
- It's a small thing, but symbolically important.

391
00:25:12,544 --> 00:25:15,445
Our parents' generation was never
interested in keeping up standards.

392
00:25:15,547 --> 00:25:20,450
They wanted to be happy, but the last way
to be happy is to make it your objective in life.

393
00:25:20,552 --> 00:25:22,782
I wonder if our generation's
any better than our parents'.

394
00:25:22,888 --> 00:25:27,791
Oh, it's far worse. Our generation's probably
the worst since the Protestant Reformation.

395
00:25:27,893 --> 00:25:32,796
It's barbaric, but a barbarism even worse
than the old-fashioned, straightforward kind.

396
00:25:32,898 --> 00:25:37,597
Now barbarism is cloaked with all sorts
of self-righteousness and moral superiority.

397
00:25:37,702 --> 00:25:41,502
- Will you look at this?
- You're obviously talking about a lot more than just detachable collars.

398
00:25:41,606 --> 00:25:42,971
Yeah, I am.

399
00:25:56,555 --> 00:25:58,614
<i>Because he's obviously
not an interesting guy.</i>

400
00:25:58,723 --> 00:26:01,123
Why is he so successful
with girls then?

401
00:26:01,226 --> 00:26:04,923
Rick Von Sloneker is tall,
rich, good-looking...

402
00:26:05,030 --> 00:26:07,260
stupid, dishonest, conceited...

403
00:26:07,365 --> 00:26:10,266
a bully, liar, drunk and thief...

404
00:26:10,368 --> 00:26:12,598
an egomaniac
and probably psychotic.

405
00:26:12,704 --> 00:26:15,002
In short,
highly attractive to women.

406
00:26:15,106 --> 00:26:18,234
You're completely unfair.
You don't know anything about Rick.

407
00:26:18,343 --> 00:26:20,903
<i>- In fact, he's quite shy.
- God!</i>

408
00:26:21,012 --> 00:26:22,912
He's a considerate and sensitive man.

409
00:26:23,014 --> 00:26:25,983
The rest is just
a superficial game he plays, a façade...

410
00:26:26,084 --> 00:26:27,984
which you've obviously
been taken in by.

411
00:26:28,086 --> 00:26:31,453
It's incredible, the eagerness of girls like you
to justify the worst bastards imaginable...

412
00:26:31,556 --> 00:26:33,683
as being sensitive and shy.

413
00:26:33,792 --> 00:26:36,693
But if any guy who really was shy
dared talk to you...

414
00:26:36,795 --> 00:26:39,696
you wouldn't give him the time of day-
your eyes would glaze over.

415
00:26:39,798 --> 00:26:42,699
You're really hung up on Rick, aren't you?
He must really threaten you somehow.

416
00:26:42,801 --> 00:26:44,701
You're right.
I do feel threatened...

417
00:26:44,803 --> 00:26:48,466
that I may get a venereal disease
from one of the St. Tim's girls he's been with.

418
00:26:50,075 --> 00:26:53,135
Did you learn that
from your lovemaking with Rick?

419
00:26:53,244 --> 00:26:55,212
I hear it can get really rough.

420
00:26:55,313 --> 00:26:58,282
- Hey!
- Don't do that again.

421
00:26:59,584 --> 00:27:01,677
For me, it isn't erotic.

422
00:27:03,955 --> 00:27:07,322
- What are you looking at?
- My father's apartment.

423
00:27:08,460 --> 00:27:10,360
<i>- Where?
- The fourth floor.</i>

424
00:27:10,462 --> 00:27:13,397
<i>- Corner apartment.
- That's Kate Preston's building.</i>

425
00:27:13,498 --> 00:27:16,262
Have your parents been divorced long?

426
00:27:16,368 --> 00:27:18,268
The actual divorce
was three years ago...

427
00:27:18,370 --> 00:27:21,271
but they were separated
for a year before that.

428
00:27:21,373 --> 00:27:24,672
- Do you see your father much?
- We have lunch when I'm in town.

429
00:27:24,776 --> 00:27:27,904
- That's very little.
- No, actually we have a very good relationship.

430
00:27:28,013 --> 00:27:30,914
Probably much better than most people
who see their father all the time.

431
00:27:31,016 --> 00:27:34,179
It's just that my stepmother is a writer
and having us around makes her nervous.

432
00:27:36,021 --> 00:27:38,888
I read that Lionel Trilling essay
you mentioned.

433
00:27:38,990 --> 00:27:41,151
- You really like Trilling?
- Yes.

434
00:27:42,193 --> 00:27:44,354
I think he's very strange.

435
00:27:44,462 --> 00:27:48,091
<i>He says that nobody could like
the heroine of Mansfield Park.</i>

436
00:27:48,199 --> 00:27:50,099
<i>I like her.</i>

437
00:27:50,201 --> 00:27:54,194
Then he goes on and on about how we modern
people of today with our modern attitudes...

438
00:27:54,305 --> 00:27:58,571
<i>bitterly resent Mansfield Park
because its heroine is virtuous?</i>

439
00:27:58,677 --> 00:28:01,578
What's wrong with a novel
having a virtuous heroine?

440
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:03,580
His point is that the novel's premise -

441
00:28:03,682 --> 00:28:07,083
that there's something immoral in a group of
young people putting on a play- is simply absurd.

442
00:28:07,185 --> 00:28:09,210
You found Fanny Price unlikable?

443
00:28:09,320 --> 00:28:11,754
She sounds pretty unbearable.
But I haven't read the book.

444
00:28:11,856 --> 00:28:15,087
- What?
- You don't have to have read a book to have an opinion on it.

445
00:28:15,193 --> 00:28:17,093
I haven't read the Bible either.

446
00:28:17,195 --> 00:28:20,062
WhatJane Austen novels have you read?

447
00:28:20,165 --> 00:28:22,065
None. I don't read novels.

448
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:24,067
I prefer good literary criticism.

449
00:28:24,169 --> 00:28:27,070
That way, you get both the novelist's ideas
as well as the critic's thinking.

450
00:28:27,172 --> 00:28:30,073
With fiction, I can never forget
that none of it ever really happened...

451
00:28:30,175 --> 00:28:32,143
that it's all just made up
by the author.

452
00:28:35,547 --> 00:28:39,039
<i>One thing I like about him is
he doesn't say all the expected things.</i>

453
00:28:39,150 --> 00:28:42,051
He doesn't just agree with everything
everyone else is saying.

454
00:28:42,153 --> 00:28:45,714
<i>That's true. He disagrees
with everything everyone else says.</i>

455
00:28:45,824 --> 00:28:47,724
I'm not sure I prefer that.

456
00:28:47,826 --> 00:28:51,023
He's quite good-looking though.
I think serious guys tend to be better-looking.

457
00:28:51,129 --> 00:28:53,256
Ow!

458
00:29:05,443 --> 00:29:10,005
The term "bourgeois" has almost always
been - been one of contempt.

459
00:29:10,115 --> 00:29:15,018
Yet it is precisely the - the bourgeoisie
which is responsible for-

460
00:29:15,120 --> 00:29:19,580
well, for nearly everything good that has happened
in our civilization over the past four centuries.

461
00:29:19,691 --> 00:29:23,320
<i>You know the French film,
The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie?</i>

462
00:29:23,428 --> 00:29:25,828
When I first heard that title I thought...

463
00:29:25,930 --> 00:29:28,922
"Finally, someone's gonna tell the truth
about the bourgeoisie. "

464
00:29:29,033 --> 00:29:31,365
<i>What a disappointment.</i>

465
00:29:31,469 --> 00:29:34,961
It would be hard to imagine
a less fair or accurate portrait.

466
00:29:35,073 --> 00:29:36,973
Well, of course.
Buñuel's a surrealist.

467
00:29:37,075 --> 00:29:40,169
<i>- Despising the bourgeoisie is part of their credo.
- Where do they get off?.</i>

468
00:29:40,278 --> 00:29:44,180
<i>But the truth is,
the bourgeoisie does have a lot of charm.</i>

469
00:29:44,282 --> 00:29:46,182
Of course it does.

470
00:29:46,284 --> 00:29:48,878
The surrealists
were just a lot of social climbers.

471
00:29:48,987 --> 00:29:50,682
Is there any more wine?

472
00:29:51,723 --> 00:29:53,623
<i>I like the French.</i>

473
00:29:53,725 --> 00:29:56,455
- Really?
- At least those I met in Grenoble.

474
00:29:56,561 --> 00:30:00,088
Actually, the only girl I ever knew who studied
in France stayed over there and got married.

475
00:30:00,198 --> 00:30:02,098
So I guess she liked the French too.

476
00:30:02,200 --> 00:30:04,828
I'm not sure I like them that much.

477
00:30:16,648 --> 00:30:19,549
<i>S.P.S., we used to call him.</i>

478
00:30:19,651 --> 00:30:22,552
Never mind.

479
00:30:22,654 --> 00:30:24,622
<i>Look.</i>

480
00:30:56,521 --> 00:31:00,048
- I think I'll visit the powder room.
- What really goes on in there?

481
00:31:00,158 --> 00:31:02,126
Oh, it's fabulous.

482
00:31:09,534 --> 00:31:12,435
You seem to be in an awfully
good mood tonight, Townsend.

483
00:31:12,537 --> 00:31:15,438
- Of course, you're in your element here.
- Are you kidding?

484
00:31:15,540 --> 00:31:18,566
You're part of it all -
the whole Manhattan thing.

485
00:31:18,676 --> 00:31:20,576
It's different for those of us
from the country.

486
00:31:20,678 --> 00:31:23,579
- You're from Greenwich.
- North Greenwich.

487
00:31:23,681 --> 00:31:26,241
- This is your world, not mine.
- Oh, come on.

488
00:31:26,351 --> 00:31:30,412
You're part of that whole Sally Fowler crowd.
Doesn't get much more inside than that.

489
00:31:30,521 --> 00:31:33,490
<i>Not that I particularly care.
I don't believe in those things.</i>

490
00:31:34,893 --> 00:31:38,795
<i>- Oh, hi, Serena.
- Hi. Hi, Tom.</i>

491
00:31:38,897 --> 00:31:41,127
- How's your brother?
- Fine.

492
00:31:42,233 --> 00:31:45,532
<i>Tom, I think we should talk.</i>

493
00:31:47,238 --> 00:31:50,935
I haven't been giving you the silent treatment.
I just haven't been talking to you.

494
00:31:51,042 --> 00:31:53,010
Well, I felt it.

495
00:31:54,412 --> 00:31:56,812
I love the St. Regis.

496
00:31:56,915 --> 00:31:59,816
There's all sorts of
hidden nooks and crannies.

497
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:01,818
It's really charming.

498
00:32:01,920 --> 00:32:04,388
Yes. They'll probably
knock it down soon.

499
00:32:12,397 --> 00:32:15,298
It hardly explains why you just left me there
waiting for you to call...

500
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:19,302
without even a phone call
to explain why you didn't show up.

501
00:32:19,404 --> 00:32:23,431
I'm sorry it was such a bad time for you, but I don't
see how that should make me feel any better.

502
00:32:23,541 --> 00:32:27,671
You don't? Well, it always
makes me feel better.

503
00:32:27,779 --> 00:32:31,510
Well, it makes me feel somewhat better,
but it still doesn't change anything.

504
00:32:31,616 --> 00:32:34,016
It shows that it wasn't intentional.

505
00:32:34,118 --> 00:32:36,313
To me,
that's an important distinction.

506
00:32:48,399 --> 00:32:50,697
Things are definitely over with Rick.

507
00:32:52,070 --> 00:32:54,971
With some relationships,
the breaking up is easier to understand...

508
00:32:55,073 --> 00:32:58,042
than how you got involved
in the first place.

509
00:33:00,979 --> 00:33:03,379
Do you think I'd have
any trouble getting a cab?

510
00:33:03,481 --> 00:33:06,211
- You're going already?
- Yes. I'm exhausted.

511
00:33:06,317 --> 00:33:10,083
My mother's doctor's been giving me these
vitamin shots. They've worn off or something.

512
00:33:18,129 --> 00:33:21,030
Oh, Fred, something's come up
and I've got to go out for a while.

513
00:33:21,132 --> 00:33:24,226
<i>Would you tell Audrey I should be back soon,
but if there's any problem I'll meet her at Sally's?</i>

514
00:33:24,335 --> 00:33:27,236
<i>Should I not get back,
could you see that she gets there okay?</i>

515
00:33:34,679 --> 00:33:36,909
Thought I was gonna puke.

516
00:33:41,219 --> 00:33:43,619
I had hardly anything to drink.

517
00:33:43,721 --> 00:33:47,680
It must have been something I ate -
those Vienna sausages.

518
00:34:02,707 --> 00:34:05,608
Actually, I was surprised to see you
at the dances this week.

519
00:34:05,710 --> 00:34:08,543
You used to be so opposed
to that sort of thing.

520
00:34:08,646 --> 00:34:10,546
I still am, basically.

521
00:34:10,648 --> 00:34:13,208
I went to the first one almost accidentally
and that night just happened to fall in...

522
00:34:13,317 --> 00:34:15,217
with an extraordinarily nice
group of people.

523
00:34:15,319 --> 00:34:17,219
Otherwise I wouldn't have
gone to any more.

524
00:34:17,321 --> 00:34:20,950
I'd hardly call Nick Smith nice.
He's a terrible snob.

525
00:34:21,059 --> 00:34:23,721
He's basically a nice guy, I think.

526
00:34:23,828 --> 00:34:25,989
His behavior toward Rick
has been vicious.

527
00:34:26,097 --> 00:34:28,588
What did he do?

528
00:34:28,699 --> 00:34:32,499
Tried to make a big stink about some girl.
Rick didn't want to talk about it.

529
00:34:32,603 --> 00:34:34,571
Apparently it was awful.

530
00:34:36,174 --> 00:34:38,335
Rick thinks Nick
could be really crazy.

531
00:34:38,443 --> 00:34:41,139
I'm just worried
that something's happened to him.

532
00:34:41,245 --> 00:34:44,146
I don't see how - how anything
could happen to him in a hotel.

533
00:34:44,248 --> 00:34:46,648
Maybe it was the same thing
that happened to Fred.

534
00:34:46,751 --> 00:34:49,151
Tom hasn't had much experience
in places like these.

535
00:34:49,253 --> 00:34:53,155
Maybe he went through one of those fire doors that
lock from the inside and shut himself in the stairwell.

536
00:34:53,257 --> 00:34:56,658
The fire stairs here aren't like that. I've had to use them
when people have forgotten to invite me to their parties.

537
00:34:56,761 --> 00:34:58,991
I've never had any trouble.

538
00:34:59,097 --> 00:35:01,497
I just don't understand
where he could be.

539
00:35:05,937 --> 00:35:07,598
Well, that - that's interesting...

540
00:35:07,705 --> 00:35:10,606
because actually there's very little
social snobbery in the United States.

541
00:35:10,708 --> 00:35:12,608
I mean, it's considered unacceptable.

542
00:35:12,710 --> 00:35:15,008
There's almost
a national taboo against it.

543
00:35:15,113 --> 00:35:18,014
- It's looked down upon.
- That's good, isn't it?

544
00:35:18,116 --> 00:35:21,017
No, I'm not talking about
what's good or bad.

545
00:35:21,119 --> 00:35:23,519
I'm just making
a- a-an observation of fact.

546
00:35:23,621 --> 00:35:25,521
<i>Well, I think it is good.</i>

547
00:35:25,623 --> 00:35:28,751
I can't stand snobbery
or snobbish attitudes of any kind.

548
00:35:29,794 --> 00:35:31,921
<i>Could you see who's there?</i>

549
00:35:38,169 --> 00:35:41,070
<i>- Sorry to be so late.
- Where were you?</i>

550
00:35:41,172 --> 00:35:43,538
- Didn't Fred tell you?
- Tell us what?

551
00:35:43,641 --> 00:35:46,542
The only thing we heard from Fred was -

552
00:35:46,644 --> 00:35:49,545
- Fred left ages ago.
- God, Audrey, I'm sorry.

553
00:35:49,647 --> 00:35:52,548
- Why?
- I asked Fred to tell you if I didn't get back-

554
00:35:52,650 --> 00:35:54,618
Don't worry.
It's nothing.

555
00:35:56,354 --> 00:35:59,255
- Well, where were you?
- I had to take Serena home.

556
00:35:59,357 --> 00:36:02,326
She was feeling badly
and she was going to go home alone.

557
00:36:09,033 --> 00:36:12,491
She's broken up with Rick.
It just took longer than I expected.

558
00:36:12,603 --> 00:36:15,504
I asked Fred to tell you that if I didn't
make it back, I'd meet you here.

559
00:36:15,606 --> 00:36:19,007
- We didn't get that message.
- We thought you'd gotten trapped somewhere in the hotel.

560
00:36:19,110 --> 00:36:21,670
<i>- Audrey was very concerned.
- I'm very sorry.</i>

561
00:36:21,779 --> 00:36:23,747
You sound very sorry.

562
00:36:26,517 --> 00:36:29,384
I find it very hard to believe
that Serena broke up with Rick.

563
00:36:29,487 --> 00:36:31,455
It was probably the other way around.

564
00:36:36,227 --> 00:36:39,890
I'm worried about Audrey.
She seems to have taken this so hard.

565
00:36:39,997 --> 00:36:41,897
I'm a bit surprised.

566
00:36:41,999 --> 00:36:44,832
I had no idea
Fred was gonna get sick.

567
00:36:44,936 --> 00:36:47,097
You know, where -
where do you get off?

568
00:36:47,205 --> 00:36:49,105
I mean, you're surprised?

569
00:36:49,207 --> 00:36:53,610
You were Audrey's escort, yet you blithely
left her stranded in the middle of the dance.

570
00:36:53,711 --> 00:36:56,111
And then you try to
shirk the whole thing off on Fred.

571
00:36:56,214 --> 00:36:59,115
I was not trying to shirk
the whole thing off on Fred.

572
00:36:59,217 --> 00:37:02,118
And I wasn't even Audrey's escort.
We were all there as a group.

573
00:37:02,220 --> 00:37:04,882
- In any case, I'm very sorry there was a mix-up.
- There was no mix-up.

574
00:37:04,989 --> 00:37:06,388
Well, it wasn't intentional.

575
00:37:06,490 --> 00:37:10,324
When you're an egoist,
none of the harm you do is intentional.

576
00:37:12,730 --> 00:37:14,630
You're going already?

577
00:37:14,732 --> 00:37:17,132
- Yes. I'm really tired.
- Just a second. I'll get my coat.

578
00:37:17,235 --> 00:37:19,135
No, that's okay.
Charlie said he'd take me.

579
00:37:19,237 --> 00:37:21,137
- I'd like to.
- No, really.

580
00:37:21,239 --> 00:37:23,139
Don't bother.

581
00:37:23,241 --> 00:37:25,641
Listen, I'm really sorry
about what happened tonight.

582
00:37:25,743 --> 00:37:28,644
- I thought I'd be back much more quickly.
- It's not important.

583
00:37:28,746 --> 00:37:30,646
- Thank you very much.
- Oh, good night.

584
00:37:30,748 --> 00:37:33,239
- You ready?
- Good night.

585
00:37:34,285 --> 00:37:36,253
- Good night, Audrey.
- Feel better.

586
00:37:37,788 --> 00:37:40,689
I never thought of myself
as a bastard, an egoist.

587
00:37:40,791 --> 00:37:42,691
Listen, don't flatter yourself.

588
00:37:42,793 --> 00:37:45,694
<i>Charlie's standard of polite behavior
is so exaggerated.</i>

589
00:37:45,796 --> 00:37:48,697
At school he used to
individually answer all his junk mail.

590
00:37:48,799 --> 00:37:52,360
I suppose he thought someone's feelings
would be hurt if he didn't.

591
00:37:52,470 --> 00:37:56,770
I like him a lot, but don't try to
understand his thought processes.

592
00:37:56,874 --> 00:37:58,774
The summer I met him -
We were 10-

593
00:37:58,876 --> 00:38:02,937
he was trying to establish communications
with the seagulls of Easthampton.

594
00:38:03,047 --> 00:38:05,948
It was utterly hopeless.
The Easthampton seagulls are complete morons.

595
00:38:06,050 --> 00:38:08,951
We still spent several afternoons
approaching shore birds, saying...

596
00:38:09,053 --> 00:38:10,953
"We come in friendship. "

597
00:38:11,055 --> 00:38:14,957
They could not have cared less - much like
his efforts with girls in recent years.

598
00:38:15,059 --> 00:38:17,687
Great. I'm hated
by the preppy St. Francis.

599
00:38:17,795 --> 00:38:19,695
I wouldn't worry about it.

600
00:38:19,797 --> 00:38:22,197
That's the building
where my father lives.

601
00:38:22,300 --> 00:38:24,928
- Do you know Kate Preston? She lives there.
- No.

602
00:38:26,804 --> 00:38:28,704
Will you look at this?

603
00:38:28,806 --> 00:38:32,207
It's incredible,
the things some people throw away.

604
00:38:32,310 --> 00:38:35,677
Steiff stuffed animals.
An Aurora model motoring set.

605
00:38:35,780 --> 00:38:38,078
A Derringer.
Do you remember the Derringer craze?

606
00:38:39,583 --> 00:38:41,483
These are the toys of our generation.

607
00:38:41,585 --> 00:38:44,486
The childhood of our whole generation
is represented here...

608
00:38:44,588 --> 00:38:47,216
and they're just throwing it out.

609
00:38:47,325 --> 00:38:50,226
Maybe we should rescue
the electric car set.

610
00:38:50,328 --> 00:38:52,455
Could really add
to these after-parties.

611
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:59,898
- Uh, I turn here.
- Oh. See you tonight.

612
00:39:00,004 --> 00:39:02,996
Listen, don't take this thing
with Charlie too seriously.

613
00:39:03,107 --> 00:39:05,075
No. See you tonight.

614
00:39:15,653 --> 00:39:20,181
My feeling is that what happened last night
had no real significance.

615
00:39:20,291 --> 00:39:22,725
It was just bad luck
that Fred got sick.

616
00:39:22,827 --> 00:39:24,795
I can't believe
you're talking like this.

617
00:39:24,895 --> 00:39:27,295
He totally humiliated you last night.

618
00:39:27,398 --> 00:39:31,494
Whether I've been humiliated or not
is something I can judge for myself.

619
00:39:31,602 --> 00:39:34,196
Besides, I don't think Tom's that way.

620
00:39:34,305 --> 00:39:37,468
<i>Well, I'm not sure
you can judge for yourself.</i>

621
00:39:37,575 --> 00:39:39,475
Be careful, Audrey.

622
00:39:39,577 --> 00:39:41,477
- There's something dubious about Tom.
- What?

623
00:39:41,579 --> 00:39:44,810
This whole thing about his being a radical
when he's obviously not...

624
00:39:44,915 --> 00:39:47,816
<i>and being over Serena
when he's obviously not.</i>

625
00:39:47,918 --> 00:39:50,284
Everyone has some contradictions.

626
00:39:50,388 --> 00:39:52,288
Anybody with
as many conflicts as Tom...

627
00:39:52,390 --> 00:39:54,881
even if he seems nice,
is better not to get involved with.

628
00:39:54,992 --> 00:39:57,392
By those standards,
none of us should get involved with anyone.

629
00:39:57,495 --> 00:39:59,554
<i>Well,you're probably right,
but in this case certainly.</i>

630
00:39:59,663 --> 00:40:03,793
Tom is the only guy I've ever liked
in my whole life.

631
00:40:03,901 --> 00:40:07,632
I'm not gonna forget about him
because of some apparent inconsistencies.

632
00:40:07,738 --> 00:40:11,139
- You hardly even know him.
- I know him very well.

633
00:40:11,242 --> 00:40:13,574
You couldn't.
You only just met him.

634
00:40:13,677 --> 00:40:16,145
Well, I do.

635
00:40:21,585 --> 00:40:23,678
I didn't know
you sent out Christmas cards.

636
00:40:23,788 --> 00:40:25,688
Well, I haven't in years.

637
00:40:25,790 --> 00:40:29,351
When we moved, do you know what happened
to my toys and things?

638
00:40:30,828 --> 00:40:32,796
They were put in storage.

639
00:40:32,897 --> 00:40:36,128
Do you think some of them
could have been sent to Dad's?

640
00:40:36,233 --> 00:40:38,793
It's possible.
Why? Do you want them?

641
00:40:38,903 --> 00:40:42,805
- You're a bit old for that sort of thing.
- No, I just had a feeling they went to Dad's.

642
00:40:42,907 --> 00:40:46,536
<i>- Well, why don't you call him then?
- I have. There's been no answer.</i>

643
00:40:55,753 --> 00:40:58,654
There's something about winter in the city
at night, with everyone dressed up...

644
00:40:58,756 --> 00:41:00,656
<i>that reminds me of War and Peace.</i>

645
00:41:00,758 --> 00:41:02,658
- Really?
- Do you know what I mean?

646
00:41:02,760 --> 00:41:06,059
Yeah, I think so,
though I haven't read it.

647
00:41:12,837 --> 00:41:15,738
Well, I don't think "preppy"
is a very useful term.

648
00:41:15,840 --> 00:41:19,037
I mean, it might be descriptive for
someone who is still in school or college...

649
00:41:19,143 --> 00:41:24,046
but it's ridiculous to refer to a man in his 7 Os,
like Averell Harriman, as a preppy.

650
00:41:24,148 --> 00:41:28,847
And none of the other terms people use -
WASP, P.L.U., et cetera - are of much use either.

651
00:41:28,953 --> 00:41:32,081
And that's why
I prefer the term "U.H.B."

652
00:41:32,189 --> 00:41:34,384
- What?
- U.H.B.

653
00:41:34,492 --> 00:41:37,552
It's an acronym for
urban haute bourgeoisie.

654
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:39,754
Is our language so impoverished...

655
00:41:39,864 --> 00:41:43,231
that we have to use acronyms or French phrases
to make ourselves understood?

656
00:41:43,334 --> 00:41:46,235
- Yes.
- U.H.B.

657
00:41:46,337 --> 00:41:49,568
The term is brilliant
and long overdue.

658
00:41:49,673 --> 00:41:52,574
But it's a bit of a mouthful, isn't it -
U.H.B.?

659
00:41:52,676 --> 00:41:57,204
Wouldn't it be better
just to pronounce it simply "UHB"?

660
00:41:57,314 --> 00:42:00,215
Well, I didn't expect it
to gain immediate acceptance.

661
00:42:00,317 --> 00:42:04,378
No, no, I think it's a useful term. The fact that
it sounds ridiculous could be part of its appeal.

662
00:42:04,488 --> 00:42:06,888
You see the world from such lofty heights...

663
00:42:06,991 --> 00:42:09,960
that everything below
is a bit comical to you, isn't it?

664
00:42:12,229 --> 00:42:14,663
- Yes.
- You're so obnoxious.

665
00:42:16,667 --> 00:42:18,567
I don't see how you can stand him.

666
00:42:18,669 --> 00:42:21,832
You're always complaining about people
being frauds and phonies.

667
00:42:21,939 --> 00:42:24,339
Well, this guy is
the phony of the decade...

668
00:42:24,441 --> 00:42:27,342
yet you act like
he was your long-lost best friend.

669
00:42:27,444 --> 00:42:31,346
Tom Townsend is hardly a phony-
just mildly deluded. He's a perfectly nice guy.

670
00:42:31,448 --> 00:42:34,906
That's just another aspect of his phoniness.
He's a complete phony.

671
00:42:35,019 --> 00:42:37,920
And when he's not being a phony,
h- he's a bastard.

672
00:42:38,022 --> 00:42:39,922
Oh, come on.

673
00:42:40,024 --> 00:42:42,925
- You saw how he treated Audrey last night.
- Audrey seems to have forgotten it.

674
00:42:43,027 --> 00:42:47,430
She has to act that way.
