How dare he hit me!

1117
01:10:19,114 --> 01:10:21,605
He's the scoundrel.
I should have thrashed him.

1118
01:10:21,717 --> 01:10:23,617
Well, you missed your chance.

1119
01:10:23,719 --> 01:10:28,850
I would have if I hadn't been doing my damnedest
not to splatter blood all over the apartment.

1120
01:10:28,958 --> 01:10:31,392
I got back, he was gone.
Nobody did anything to help me.

1121
01:10:31,493 --> 01:10:33,961
I'm facing one of the worst guys
of modern times...

1122
01:10:34,063 --> 01:10:36,429
and all I get's this whining criticism -

1123
01:10:36,532 --> 01:10:38,762
"Oh, this looks really bad, Nick. "

1124
01:10:38,867 --> 01:10:41,165
Why should we believe you over Rick?

1125
01:10:41,270 --> 01:10:45,297
We know you're a hypocrite. We know
your Polly Perkins story was a fabrication.

1126
01:10:45,407 --> 01:10:47,967
A composite!

1127
01:10:48,077 --> 01:10:51,069
That you're totally impossible and out of control
with some sort of drug problem...

1128
01:10:51,180 --> 01:10:54,013
and a fixation on what you consider
Rick Von Sloneker's wickedness.

1129
01:10:54,116 --> 01:10:58,018
<i>You're a snob, a sexist,
totally obnoxious and tiresome...</i>

1130
01:10:58,120 --> 01:11:00,088
and, lately, you've gotten just weird.

1131
01:11:00,189 --> 01:11:04,785
- Why should we believe anything you say?
- I am not tiresome.

1132
01:11:04,893 --> 01:11:06,861
What's Rick to you anyway?

1133
01:11:06,962 --> 01:11:08,987
Your shy friend hits me in the face...

1134
01:11:09,098 --> 01:11:13,057
I'm about to go upstate to the domain of
a stepmother of untrammeled malevolence...

1135
01:11:13,168 --> 01:11:15,136
very possibly to be killed...

1136
01:11:15,237 --> 01:11:17,467
and I get this.

1137
01:11:17,573 --> 01:11:20,371
Well, who could blame her?

1138
01:11:20,476 --> 01:11:24,913
If not spattering blood was your objective,
you weren't terribly successful.

1139
01:11:28,851 --> 01:11:31,149
Well...

1140
01:11:31,253 --> 01:11:33,346
I'm going to Grand Central.

1141
01:11:33,455 --> 01:11:35,389
The people are friendlier.

1142
01:11:35,491 --> 01:11:37,891
I'll help you with your stuff.

1143
01:11:38,927 --> 01:11:41,555
Why don't we all go see Nick off?

1144
01:11:51,840 --> 01:11:55,298
Even within this group,
there are certain standards.

1145
01:11:55,411 --> 01:11:58,380
Apparently,
I failed to live up to them.

1146
01:12:01,817 --> 01:12:06,277
- Thanks for coming. Will you write?
- Yes.

1147
01:12:06,388 --> 01:12:08,982
- Good-bye. Thanks for coming.
- Good-bye, sir.

1148
01:12:10,025 --> 01:12:11,959
- Good-bye, Tom.
- Good luck.

1149
01:12:12,061 --> 01:12:16,930
I leave, counting on you and Charlie to maintain
the standards and ideals of the U.H.B.

1150
01:12:17,032 --> 01:12:19,000
I've obviously failed to.

1151
01:12:19,101 --> 01:12:21,729
You and Charlie are the only ones
who understand this kind of thing.

1152
01:12:21,837 --> 01:12:23,805
- What?
- Here.

1153
01:12:23,906 --> 01:12:26,067
Thank you.

1154
01:12:26,175 --> 01:12:28,643
- Oh. Also, you remember, in case I die -
- Yes.

1155
01:12:28,744 --> 01:12:31,178
- All right. Good-bye.
- Bye.

1156
01:12:31,280 --> 01:12:33,180
<i>- Bye.
- Good-bye.</i>

1157
01:13:00,976 --> 01:13:03,945
Is the 21 Club very expensive?

1158
01:13:04,046 --> 01:13:05,946
<i>I believe so.</i>

1159
01:13:08,117 --> 01:13:09,744
That's priceless.

1160
01:13:09,852 --> 01:13:13,151
And then she told Miss Radford,
"They look awfully big for mice. "

1161
01:13:13,255 --> 01:13:15,155
- She believed it?
- Oh, completely.

1162
01:13:15,257 --> 01:13:17,157
Oh, that's priceless.

1163
01:13:17,259 --> 01:13:20,126
You mentioned something about it
in one of your letters.

1164
01:13:20,229 --> 01:13:23,687
When I was going through some stuff over
Christmas, I found a packet of your old letters.

1165
01:13:23,799 --> 01:13:26,563
- You saved my letters?
- Of course.

1166
01:13:26,668 --> 01:13:30,195
I save all the personal letters I get.
Don't you?

1167
01:13:30,305 --> 01:13:33,001
No.

1168
01:13:33,108 --> 01:13:35,633
You mean, you threw away
all the letters I wrote you?

1169
01:13:35,744 --> 01:13:37,712
I throw away nearly everything.

1170
01:13:37,813 --> 01:13:41,476
I don't want to go through the rest of my life
with the mail I got when I was 16.

1171
01:13:41,583 --> 01:13:43,483
I'm surprised.

1172
01:13:43,585 --> 01:13:47,214
Someone goes through the trouble
of writing you a real letter, I save it.

1173
01:13:47,322 --> 01:13:49,449
People don't write
many personal letters anymore.

1174
01:13:49,558 --> 01:13:52,118
People in boarding school do.

1175
01:13:53,829 --> 01:13:56,024
And what if someone who wrote you
becomes famous?

1176
01:13:56,131 --> 01:14:00,261
Those letters could be the only record of what they were
thinking at that time. Crucial for their biographers.

1177
01:14:00,369 --> 01:14:03,861
Anybody who writes me who expects
to become famous should keep carbons.

1178
01:14:05,841 --> 01:14:08,469
It just seems to me
that it's a kind of trust.

1179
01:14:08,577 --> 01:14:13,480
If someone takes the trouble to write you
a substantial letter, you do not throw it out.

1180
01:14:14,850 --> 01:14:18,217
I didn't save your letters,
but I didn't throw them out.

1181
01:14:18,320 --> 01:14:21,653
I don't understand.
Is that a riddle?

1182
01:14:21,757 --> 01:14:25,284
<i>There was a girl at school
who had some kind of a crush on you.</i>

1183
01:14:25,394 --> 01:14:29,455
She came into my room when I was throwing
things out, so I gave her your letters.

1184
01:14:29,565 --> 01:14:31,465
Really?

1185
01:14:31,567 --> 01:14:34,695
I know it sounds queer.

1186
01:14:34,803 --> 01:14:38,000
- She kept them?
- Mmm. I'm sure.

1187
01:14:38,106 --> 01:14:40,836
How strange.
She must be really odd.

1188
01:14:40,943 --> 01:14:43,741
No, she's very nice.

1189
01:14:43,846 --> 01:14:46,610
In fact, you know her.

1190
01:14:46,715 --> 01:14:48,615
Audrey Rouget.

1191
01:14:55,157 --> 01:14:58,854
You mean, you think
you've gotten over Serena again.

1192
01:14:58,961 --> 01:15:00,929
Yes, but it's different this time.

1193
01:15:01,029 --> 01:15:05,125
Then I was still intensely involved with her,
though in a negative way. Full of bitterness.

1194
01:15:05,234 --> 01:15:07,361
I don't feel that way now.

1195
01:15:07,469 --> 01:15:10,165
<i>Charlie's on his way up.</i>

1196
01:15:10,272 --> 01:15:12,467
Damn. There's something
I wanted to ask you.

1197
01:15:12,574 --> 01:15:15,099
Oh, yeah. What was that surprising thing
Serena told you?

1198
01:15:15,210 --> 01:15:19,078
Well, you probably already knew about it, but I was surprised
- about Audrey saving my letters.

1199
01:15:19,181 --> 01:15:22,639
<i>- What letters?
- The ones I wrote Serena.</i>

1200
01:15:22,751 --> 01:15:24,946
Audrey saved them?

1201
01:15:26,054 --> 01:15:27,954
God, how queer.

1202
01:15:28,056 --> 01:15:29,990
Well, it's not so queer really.

1203
01:15:30,092 --> 01:15:31,957
Serena was about to throw them out...

1204
01:15:32,060 --> 01:15:34,858
and Audrey apparently didn't think
people's letters should be destroyed that way.

1205
01:15:34,963 --> 01:15:39,662
The really odd thing was though, while I was with
Serena, who's really nice and who's so good-looking -

1206
01:15:39,768 --> 01:15:41,759
Yeah, Serena's basically a good person.

1207
01:15:41,870 --> 01:15:44,168
On the big night
I'd looked forward to for a week...

1208
01:15:44,273 --> 01:15:47,174
I started feeling this incredible loneliness
being with Serena...

1209
01:15:47,276 --> 01:15:50,404
and nostalgia for all those conversations
with Audrey before the big blowup.

1210
01:15:50,512 --> 01:15:52,742
That was before I knew anything
about the letters.

1211
01:15:52,848 --> 01:15:56,978
<i>I think I preferred arguing with Audrey
than to agreeing with Serena or someone else.</i>

1212
01:15:57,085 --> 01:16:01,749
I'd only had that calmly unemotional perspective
on my relationship with Serena for a little while...

1213
01:16:01,857 --> 01:16:06,260
<i>when I started getting this warm glow at
the prospect of seeing Audrey here again tonight.</i>

1214
01:16:06,361 --> 01:16:08,124
Uh-oh.

1215
01:16:08,230 --> 01:16:12,860
It surprised me because I thought that if-
if it didn't work out with Serena this time...

1216
01:16:12,968 --> 01:16:15,869
I'd put that sort of thing
on hold for a long time.

1217
01:16:15,971 --> 01:16:18,997
People shouldn't get married till their late 20s,
and that's a long way off.

1218
01:16:19,107 --> 01:16:22,076
- Well, your timing is really awful.
- What do you mean?

1219
01:16:26,081 --> 01:16:29,380
Damn. I'll get it.
I want to continue this.

1220
01:16:35,090 --> 01:16:37,388
- Where's Jane?
- She's still in her room.

1221
01:16:37,492 --> 01:16:39,960
- What would you like to drink?
- So you're our host?

1222
01:16:40,062 --> 01:16:42,496
I don't know. What do people
who don't drink have?

1223
01:16:42,598 --> 01:16:47,399
Ginger ale? Ice water?
Ah, maybe a Coke with an aspirin.

1224
01:16:48,570 --> 01:16:51,198
You don't need to put on
pink eye shadow for us.

1225
01:16:51,306 --> 01:16:53,934
It's not for you.
I've got a date.

1226
01:16:54,042 --> 01:16:57,671
A date? What's that?
It sounds like something from the 1950s.

1227
01:16:57,779 --> 01:16:59,679
Yeah. Who's the fella?

1228
01:16:59,781 --> 01:17:02,978
None of you know him,
and I'd like to keep it that way.

1229
01:17:07,356 --> 01:17:10,450
What did you mean when you said that
about my timing being off?

1230
01:17:10,559 --> 01:17:13,255
Audrey's gone to Cynthia's
in Connecticut for the weekend...

1231
01:17:13,362 --> 01:17:15,557
and then on Wednesday
she flies back to France.

1232
01:17:15,664 --> 01:17:17,655
And besides that,
she thinks you're a total jerk.

1233
01:17:17,766 --> 01:17:18,960
<i>- She hates you.
- She hates me?</i>

1234
01:17:19,067 --> 01:17:22,161
Well, she despises you.
Actually, it's a bit my fault.

1235
01:17:22,270 --> 01:17:24,830
<i>I asked for that Truth question
with a specific idea in mind...</i>

1236
01:17:24,940 --> 01:17:27,340
<i>of showing her
you hadn't gotten over Serena yet.</i>

1237
01:17:27,643 --> 01:17:31,670
- A Mr. Andrews is downstairs for you.
- Say I'll be right down.

1238
01:17:31,780 --> 01:17:34,010
- We'll go down with you.
- No, you won't.

1239
01:17:34,116 --> 01:17:36,516
- We can all go out together.
- No. This is a date.

1240
01:17:36,618 --> 01:17:39,086
Well, it seems rude
not to go down and check him out.

1241
01:17:39,187 --> 01:17:44,056
Please don't. Feel free to stay here.
There's plenty of food and stuff.

1242
01:17:44,159 --> 01:17:47,219
But it's all right if we stay here
and wait for everyone else?

1243
01:17:47,329 --> 01:17:49,559
Sure, but what "everyone else"?

1244
01:17:50,899 --> 01:17:53,333
Well, the rest of the S.F.R.P.

1245
01:17:53,435 --> 01:17:56,063
You are the S.F.R.P. tonight.

1246
01:17:56,171 --> 01:18:00,232
Oh, could you be out by midnight?
Feel free to stay until then though. Bye!

1247
01:18:00,342 --> 01:18:02,242
- Bye.
- Bye.

1248
01:18:02,344 --> 01:18:06,405
Bye. Be out by midnight?
What's going on?

1249
01:18:06,515 --> 01:18:10,713
Jane brings this guy she hardly knows
back for some kind of assignation?

1250
01:18:10,819 --> 01:18:13,253
- We don't know that.
- Well -

1251
01:18:13,355 --> 01:18:15,516
I'm really surprised atJane.

1252
01:18:15,624 --> 01:18:18,388
Some guy asks her out,
and she abandons everything.

1253
01:18:18,493 --> 01:18:21,792
The rest of us can, well,
just go to heck.

1254
01:18:21,897 --> 01:18:24,923
The whole Rat Pack thing
seems to have disintegrated.

1255
01:18:25,033 --> 01:18:27,968
The Rat Pack is down to the rats.

1256
01:18:28,070 --> 01:18:31,597
This is really depressing.
Let's get out of here.

1257
01:18:37,713 --> 01:18:40,739
I guess it's understandable that she
would prefer to go out on a date...

1258
01:18:40,849 --> 01:18:45,149
which offers some romantic promise,
even if very slight, than stay with us.

1259
01:18:45,253 --> 01:18:49,314
Still, it's a bit disappointing.
I thought we were better friends than that.

1260
01:18:49,424 --> 01:18:51,949
I wonder whether
we're really friends for them at all.

1261
01:18:52,060 --> 01:18:54,187
We're just way stations
between dates.

1262
01:18:54,296 --> 01:18:59,097
I mean, for them, men are either dates,
potential dates or date substitutes.

1263
01:18:59,201 --> 01:19:01,226
I find that dehumanizing.

1264
01:19:01,336 --> 01:19:04,567
That might be the case
with Cynthia or Sally...

1265
01:19:04,673 --> 01:19:06,868
but Audrey, for instance,
is completely different.

1266
01:19:06,975 --> 01:19:09,876
She's someone who would keep up
her friendships no matter what.

1267
01:19:09,978 --> 01:19:14,438
And Audrey has a rare largeness of mind.
She's not obsessed with her love life.

1268
01:19:14,549 --> 01:19:18,076
She's good-looking, smart...

1269
01:19:18,186 --> 01:19:20,620
charming, principled.

1270
01:19:20,722 --> 01:19:22,690
It's an unusual combination.

1271
01:19:28,096 --> 01:19:29,996
<i>What do you mean?</i>

1272
01:19:30,098 --> 01:19:33,295
<i>You've given her nothing but grief all the past week.
- I think I'll be going now.</i>

1273
01:19:33,401 --> 01:19:36,928
I have nothing to say,
and I'm completely boring without a drink.

1274
01:19:37,038 --> 01:19:39,506
It's only midnight.
You can't go.

1275
01:19:39,608 --> 01:19:44,102
I'm sorry, but without cocktails,
staying up all night loses its charm.

1276
01:19:44,212 --> 01:19:47,181
Besides, I haven't had anything amusing
to say since I stopped drinking.

1277
01:19:47,282 --> 01:19:50,274
Did you have anything amusing to say
before you stopped?

1278
01:19:50,385 --> 01:19:53,081
I know, but it seemed amusing.
Now it doesn't.

1279
01:19:53,188 --> 01:19:56,282
- Well, you were asleep.
- Was that it?

1280
01:19:56,391 --> 01:20:00,293
- Good night, Charlie. Ciao, Tommy.
- Ciao, Fred.

1281
01:20:01,930 --> 01:20:06,526
<i>?I won't be loved, baby?</i>

1282
01:20:06,635 --> 01:20:10,435
When I was in college, we'd go to dances
during Christmas vacations.

1283
01:20:10,539 --> 01:20:13,337
- Do they still go on?
- Yes.

1284
01:20:13,441 --> 01:20:16,205
- Pretty much reduced though.
- Yeah.

1285
01:20:16,311 --> 01:20:18,575
<i>Ah, well, I wouldn't put
much stock in them.</i>

1286
01:20:18,680 --> 01:20:21,308
You go to a party, you meet a group
of people, you like them, you think...

1287
01:20:21,416 --> 01:20:24,783
"These people are going to be my friends
for the rest of my life. "

1288
01:20:24,886 --> 01:20:28,822
Then you never see them again.
I wonder where they go.

1289
01:20:28,924 --> 01:20:31,392
Do you think it's true, though,
that, generally speaking...

1290
01:20:31,493 --> 01:20:33,927
people from this sort of background
are doomed to failure?

1291
01:20:34,029 --> 01:20:36,657
Doomed?
That would, uh, be far easier.

1292
01:20:36,765 --> 01:20:40,326
No, we simply fail
without being doomed.

1293
01:20:40,435 --> 01:20:43,836
- But you feel that you have failed.
- Yeah.

1294
01:20:43,939 --> 01:20:45,998
You can still afford
to come to places like this though.

1295
01:20:46,107 --> 01:20:49,235
<i>I'm not destitute.
I've got a goodjob that pays decently.</i>

1296
01:20:49,344 --> 01:20:53,940
It's just that it's all so mediocre,
so unimpressive.

1297
01:20:54,049 --> 01:20:58,179
The acid test is whether you take any pleasure
in responding to the question...

1298
01:20:58,286 --> 01:21:00,754
"What do you do?"

1299
01:21:00,856 --> 01:21:03,552
I can't bear it.

1300
01:21:03,658 --> 01:21:08,561
You start out expecting something much more,
and some of your contemporaries achieve it.

1301
01:21:08,663 --> 01:21:12,030
You start reading about them in the papers
or seeing them on TV.

1302
01:21:12,133 --> 01:21:14,431
That's the danger
of midtown Manhattan -

1303
01:21:14,536 --> 01:21:17,767
running across
far more successful contemporaries.

1304
01:21:17,873 --> 01:21:20,967
I try to avoid them whenever I can.

1305
01:21:21,076 --> 01:21:24,773
But when I can't,
they're always very friendly...

1306
01:21:24,880 --> 01:21:28,577
but inevitably they ask,
what am I doing, or think it.

1307
01:21:28,683 --> 01:21:32,710
I - I find it hard to believe that many people
from our background are successful.

1308
01:21:32,821 --> 01:21:36,052
Aren't you confusing them with people
that you might have known from college...

1309
01:21:36,157 --> 01:21:38,387
who came from normal backgrounds?

1310
01:21:38,493 --> 01:21:43,294
It's not surprising that -
that an energetic, self-confident achiever...

1311
01:21:43,398 --> 01:21:45,366
free of UHB illusions...

1312
01:21:45,467 --> 01:21:47,435
should be successful.

1313
01:21:47,535 --> 01:21:49,469
- UHB? What's UHB?
- UHB.

1314
01:21:49,571 --> 01:21:53,837
U.H.B. It's an acronym
for Urban Haute Bourgeoisie.

1315
01:21:53,942 --> 01:21:57,036
It's a more sociologically precise
alternative...

1316
01:21:57,145 --> 01:21:59,978
to "preppy" and other terms.

1317
01:22:00,081 --> 01:22:02,641
Well, you're partly right.

1318
01:22:02,751 --> 01:22:06,346
Some of the people whom I mentioned
were not from... UHB?

1319
01:22:06,454 --> 01:22:08,922
- That's right.
- UHB backgrounds, but some of them were.

1320
01:22:09,024 --> 01:22:12,152
You're going to have to accept
that people from our background...

1321
01:22:12,260 --> 01:22:14,990
are not doomed to failure.

1322
01:22:16,932 --> 01:22:20,060
I - I wonder if they were typical UHBs.

1323
01:22:20,168 --> 01:22:24,366
There was -There was probably
some factor which set them apart.

1324
01:22:24,472 --> 01:22:26,599
And, also, their-
their career is not over.

1325
01:22:26,708 --> 01:22:29,006
I mean, the failure
could still be to come.

1326
01:22:37,185 --> 01:22:41,144
- He seems less pessimistic than you.
- I know. It doesn't ring true.

1327
01:22:46,661 --> 01:22:48,561
Look, there's a light on.

1328
01:22:48,663 --> 01:22:51,029
We can't go up to her place
unannounced after midnight.

1329
01:22:51,132 --> 01:22:54,761
- It all depends who's on the elevator.
- It's not a question of who's on the elevator.

1330
01:22:54,869 --> 01:22:56,928
I mean, you've known Sally
for, what, 10 days?

1331
01:22:57,038 --> 01:22:59,506
And you're barging in on her uninvited
in the middle of the night?

1332
01:22:59,607 --> 01:23:03,509
She said we should come up anytime we saw the
living room lights on, which they clearly are.

1333
01:23:03,611 --> 01:23:06,136
- At least call first.
- What, and wake up her parents?

1334
01:23:06,247 --> 01:23:08,715
Well, you act as if her apartment
were our living room.

1335
01:23:08,817 --> 01:23:10,785
<i>It is our living room.</i>

1336
01:23:11,820 --> 01:23:13,720
<i>Thanks, Ed.</i>

1337
01:23:16,791 --> 01:23:20,090
- What are we doing here?
- It'll be all right.

1338
01:23:22,964 --> 01:23:26,923
- What are you doing here?
- You told us to come up if we saw the lights on.

1339
01:23:27,035 --> 01:23:30,402
- I'm sorry to bother you.
- I was just about to go out.

1340
01:23:30,505 --> 01:23:33,269
<i>- Oh.
- Who is it?</i>

1341
01:23:33,375 --> 01:23:36,173
Just some friends.

1342
01:23:36,277 --> 01:23:38,177
Well, come on in.

1343
01:23:42,484 --> 01:23:45,942
<i>Allen, these are my friends,
Charlie and Tommy.</i>

1344
01:23:46,054 --> 01:23:48,955
Allen is the record producer
who discovered The Hated Few.

1345
01:23:49,057 --> 01:23:51,617
- They're very good.
- Yes, they are.

1346
01:23:51,726 --> 01:23:55,127
And Sally will be very good.
She's got a wonderful voice.

1347
01:23:55,230 --> 01:23:58,666
<i>I think we also have a friend in common-
Rick Von Sloneker.</i>

1348
01:23:58,767 --> 01:24:01,292
Yeah. You're a friend of Rick's?

1349
01:24:01,403 --> 01:24:04,930
Oh, sure. Rick's a great guy. Our houses
are next to each other in Southampton.

1350
01:24:05,040 --> 01:24:07,508
Wow, it's late.
Uh, we'd better get going.

1351
01:24:07,609 --> 01:24:10,237
I don't think there's time for drinks
after all.

1352
01:24:15,650 --> 01:24:19,518
Do you have any idea when everyone's getting back?
It's as if the whole S.F.R.P. had disintegrated.

1353
01:24:19,621 --> 01:24:23,580
We can't just keep getting together with the same
people every night for the rest of our lives.

1354
01:24:23,691 --> 01:24:25,591
I don't see why not.

1355
01:24:25,693 --> 01:24:28,161
It's inevitable that things
get more back to normal sometime.

1356
01:24:28,263 --> 01:24:30,458
- This wasn't normal?
- No.

1357
01:24:30,565 --> 01:24:32,692
I wish somebody
had told me that before.

1358
01:24:32,801 --> 01:24:35,269
Could you tell me, at least,
when Cynthia and Audrey are getting back?

1359
01:24:35,370 --> 01:24:37,600
I don't know. That's their affair.

1360
01:24:37,705 --> 01:24:40,105
<i>- Your friend Cynthia's gone to that house party at Rick's.
- In Southampton?</i>

1361
01:24:40,208 --> 01:24:42,335
<i>- Uh-huh.
- I'm not sure if she was really going.</i>

1362
01:24:42,444 --> 01:24:44,412
<i>You guys are so tiresome.</i>

1363
01:24:59,727 --> 01:25:02,457
That was really embarrassing.
Thank you for including me.

1364
01:25:02,564 --> 01:25:04,498
I can't believe it. God!

1365
01:25:04,599 --> 01:25:08,729
Maybe, underneath it all, he's a nice guy, but he
sure doesn't make a very good first impression.

1366
01:25:08,837 --> 01:25:11,499
- No, not about that. What he said about Cynthia.
- Oh.

1367
01:25:11,606 --> 01:25:14,131
Look, if Audrey's supposed to be
visiting Cynthia in Connecticut...

1368
01:25:14,242 --> 01:25:17,006
and Cynthia's in Southampton
with Von Sloneker, what does that mean?

1369
01:25:17,112 --> 01:25:19,410
That Audrey and Cynthia
are in different states.

1370
01:25:19,514 --> 01:25:21,414
No. There's only one explanation.

1371
01:25:21,516 --> 01:25:25,475
Audrey has gone with Cynthia
to Von Sloneker's house party in Southampton.

1372
01:25:25,587 --> 01:25:28,920
You know, you're always
selling Audrey awfully short, aren't you?

1373
01:25:29,023 --> 01:25:31,787
I mean, I find that - that
really despicable.

1374
01:25:31,893 --> 01:25:34,919
Could you stop calling me despicable?
I'm really worried about Audrey.

1375
01:25:35,029 --> 01:25:37,691
Jane says that since that Truth session,
she's been in a very strange mood...

1376
01:25:37,799 --> 01:25:39,767
and said some really odd things.

1377
01:25:39,868 --> 01:25:42,302
She told Jane she didn't feel
like a real woman.

1378
01:25:42,403 --> 01:25:44,803
- She said that?
- That's the way Cynthia talks.

1379
01:25:44,906 --> 01:25:46,806
Yeah.

1380
01:25:46,908 --> 01:25:49,672
I can't - I can't really share
your concern.

1381
01:25:49,777 --> 01:25:53,076
I mean, Audrey wouldn't put herself
in the situation you describe.

1382
01:25:53,181 --> 01:25:55,809
She's got very, very clear views
on these things.

1383
01:25:55,917 --> 01:25:58,647
I mean, you know that -
that she's a big admirer ofJane Austen.

1384
01:25:58,753 --> 01:26:02,120
- But she's turned her back on all that.
- Oh, I don't believe that.

1385
01:26:02,223 --> 01:26:04,191
She's probably at home,
asleep right now...

1386
01:26:04,292 --> 01:26:07,887
with her pink coverlet tucked up tight
and her stuffed animals looking down over her.

1387
01:26:07,996 --> 01:26:10,863
- Well, let's call her then.
- We can't.

1388
01:26:10,965 --> 01:26:15,334
- It's only a local call.
- We can't call her up now. It's nearly 3:00 a. m.

1389
01:26:15,436 --> 01:26:17,563
We'd -We'd wake up her parents.

1390
01:26:17,672 --> 01:26:20,641
This is important to them too.
What if she's already at Von Sloneker's?

1391
01:26:20,742 --> 01:26:22,710
I'm sure he's not asleep.

1392
01:26:25,046 --> 01:26:28,072
Older people tend to get up really early.
I'll call the Rougets at 7:00.

1393
01:26:28,183 --> 01:26:32,620
If there's any risk of Audrey going out
to Von Sloneker's, I'll give you a call.

1394
01:26:32,720 --> 01:26:35,450
But - But I don't expect to have to.

1395
01:26:35,557 --> 01:26:37,457
Could you call me either way?

1396
01:26:37,559 --> 01:26:40,551
At 7:00? Okay.

1397
01:26:40,662 --> 01:26:42,926
Thanks.
You're not such a bad fellow.

1398
01:26:43,031 --> 01:26:45,693
- I'll call you.
- Call me.

1399
01:26:57,912 --> 01:27:00,176
I hate him.

1400
01:27:02,517 --> 01:27:04,917
<i>- Audrey Rouget?
- Uh-huh.</i>

1401
01:27:05,019 --> 01:27:08,978
- She's getting very attractive.
- She was the first girl that ever made him feel that way.

1402
01:27:09,090 --> 01:27:11,456
She thinks you're a total jerk.
She hates you.

1403
01:27:11,559 --> 01:27:14,289
When you're an egoist,
none of the harm you do is intentional.

1404
01:27:14,395 --> 01:27:19,332
- Well, she despises you.
- Him. Victor Lemley, the other crew member.

1405
01:27:19,434 --> 01:27:23,393
- I want to be a real woman.
- You're the only girl who's ever made me feel this way.

1406
01:27:23,504 --> 01:27:26,268
I had nothing to do with that,
and, anyway, she was completely unstable.

1407
01:27:26,374 --> 01:27:28,342
I want to be a real woman.

1408
01:27:37,518 --> 01:27:40,214
I called Audrey's parents
exactly at 7:00.

1409
01:27:40,321 --> 01:27:42,755
It turns out that they're
not - not such early risers.

1410
01:27:42,857 --> 01:27:46,884
But they- they thought that Audrey
was with Cynthia in Connecticut too.

1411
01:27:46,995 --> 01:27:49,862
So I called Cynthia's,
and her mother answered.

1412
01:27:49,964 --> 01:27:51,932
Apparently,
she was sleeping late also.

1413
01:27:52,033 --> 01:27:55,969
But she said that Cynthia
was visiting Audrey.

1414
01:27:56,070 --> 01:27:59,801
- Jesus!
- Well, Cynthia borrowed her mother's car.

1415
01:27:59,907 --> 01:28:02,341
And the last anyone has seen
of either of them...

1416
01:28:02,443 --> 01:28:04,411
was about 4:00 yesterday afternoon.

1417
01:28:04,512 --> 01:28:07,481
So they might have gotten
to Von Sloneker's already last night.

1418
01:28:07,582 --> 01:28:09,550
You were right.

1419
01:28:14,122 --> 01:28:16,420
But I am authorized
to use my mother's card.

1420
01:28:16,524 --> 01:28:18,958
I use it all the time.

1421
01:28:21,129 --> 01:28:23,563
- She wasn't very polite.
- No, she wasn't.

1422
01:28:25,600 --> 01:28:27,568
That should be plenty.

1423
01:28:33,207 --> 01:28:34,834
Yeah.

1424
01:28:40,882 --> 01:28:44,682
- I can't believe you don't have a license.
- Of course I don't. I live in Manhattan.

1425
01:28:44,786 --> 01:28:47,778
- I'm just really surprised, that's all.
- Oh, give me a break.

1426
01:28:47,889 --> 01:28:50,858
I don't go out to the Hamptons.
You could have gotten one easily.

1427
01:28:50,958 --> 01:28:54,086
- I'm no jock.
- God, what a disaster.

1428
01:28:54,195 --> 01:28:56,959
No, I'm -
I'm gonna get a license soon.

1429
01:28:58,333 --> 01:29:00,631
This must be how
the - the, um, failure starts -

1430
01:29:00,735 --> 01:29:04,535
an incompetence in mastering
the common tasks of everyday life.

1431
01:29:04,639 --> 01:29:07,733
- Doesn't Fred have a license?
- Yeah.

1432
01:29:07,842 --> 01:29:09,742
Okay.

1433
01:29:10,812 --> 01:29:12,712
Bye.

1434
01:29:13,781 --> 01:29:17,080
He says he can't.
He's about to get fired as it is.

1435
01:29:17,185 --> 01:29:19,210
He was always saying
what a lousy job it was.

1436
01:29:19,320 --> 01:29:22,346
- Did you tell him how serious the situation is?
- Yes.

1437
01:29:23,791 --> 01:29:27,192
He's always complaining
about what a lousy job it is.

1438
01:29:27,295 --> 01:29:30,731
You know, it's possible that, to other people,
the situation might not seem so ominous...

1439
01:29:30,832 --> 01:29:32,800
<i>as it does to you and me.</i>

1440
01:29:32,900 --> 01:29:36,028
<i>I- I mean, what can really happen?</i>

1441
01:29:36,137 --> 01:29:39,106
Of course, you have been right up till now,
and Von Sloneker is a bad guy...

1442
01:29:39,207 --> 01:29:41,107
I mean, capable of anything.

1443
01:29:41,209 --> 01:29:44,474
It might sound melodramatic
to say that he's ruined girls.

1444
01:29:44,579 --> 01:29:47,548
<i>I mean, what does that
really mean today?</i>

1445
01:29:47,648 --> 01:29:51,140
But it's true. I mean,
he's done some unspeakable things.

1446
01:29:51,252 --> 01:29:54,813
<i>And if Audrey's as upset and bitter as it seems,
well, then anything could happen.</i>

1447
01:29:55,990 --> 01:29:57,958
We gotta get out there
as fast as possible.

1448
01:29:58,059 --> 01:30:01,460
While we sit here, flailing around, anything
could be happening out at Von Sloneker's.

1449
01:30:01,562 --> 01:30:03,928
If only Nick were here.
He'd know what to do.

1450
01:30:04,031 --> 01:30:06,499
Yeah, he's got all sorts
of licenses and credit cards.

1451
01:30:06,601 --> 01:30:09,570
<i>What would Nick do?
How would he get out of this?</i>

1452
01:30:11,272 --> 01:30:14,002
You've got a lot of cash on you now.

1453
01:30:14,108 --> 01:30:16,269
Yes. Lots.

1454
01:30:50,578 --> 01:30:53,945
Whenever I think we might be overreacting,
I remember Polly Perkins.

1455
01:30:54,048 --> 01:30:57,848
- Or Cathy Livingstone.
- I think I knew her.

1456
01:30:59,821 --> 01:31:02,119
What are you gonna do
when we get there?

1457
01:31:02,223 --> 01:31:05,249
I don't know.
It depends on what the situation is.

1458
01:31:08,396 --> 01:31:12,355
Yesterday I was thinking,
maybe Fourier was a crank...

1459
01:31:12,467 --> 01:31:14,901
his ideas completely unworkable.

1460
01:31:15,002 --> 01:31:18,836
I wouldn't want to live on a farm
with a lot of other people.

1461
01:31:22,977 --> 01:31:26,413
You know, Rick's a strange guy.
He's pretty violent.

1462
01:31:28,115 --> 01:31:30,640
He might not be
too pleased to see us.

1463
01:31:30,751 --> 01:31:32,719
I've thought of that.

1464
01:32:11,359 --> 01:32:13,486
Thanks a lot.
We shouldn't be long.

1465
01:32:13,594 --> 01:32:16,791
Well, take as long as you want.
I'm leaving.

1466
01:32:16,898 --> 01:32:21,426
Oh, no. Um, we need you to take us back.
That -That was understood.

1467
01:32:21,536 --> 01:32:24,027
Think I'm gonna wait around
for you guys? You're crazy.

1468
01:32:31,145 --> 01:32:34,672
But I - I don't know how
we're going to get back.

1469
01:32:34,782 --> 01:32:36,977
What's this shit?

1470
01:32:37,084 --> 01:32:39,746
- Oh, a gratuity is included.
- What's this shit?

1471
01:32:47,628 --> 01:32:50,756
I was sure th-that we agreed
on 120 as the full price.

1472
01:32:58,072 --> 01:33:01,098
- Hey, look at this.
- What is it?

1473
01:33:01,208 --> 01:33:03,904
- Looks like some girl's panties.
- Jesus. That bastard.

1474
01:33:41,215 --> 01:33:44,446
<i>What are you clowns doing here?</i>

1475
01:33:44,552 --> 01:33:46,884
<i>- What are you doing?
- This is my place.</i>

1476
01:33:46,988 --> 01:33:49,718
- I can do whatever I want here.
- That's not true.

1477
01:33:49,824 --> 01:33:52,816
<i>How dare you break in here?
Did they break that?</i>

1478
01:33:52,927 --> 01:33:55,157
What are you doing here?
This is so embarrassing.

1479
01:33:55,262 --> 01:33:58,129
A little embarrassment
could do you some good.

1480
01:33:58,232 --> 01:34:00,530
And by the way, whose are these?

1481
01:34:00,635 --> 01:34:03,502
I haven't the slightest idea.
Just get out of here, you twerps!

1482
01:34:03,604 --> 01:34:08,132
<i>- They buy them new and scatter them around. It's one of Rick's little delicacies.
- That's a lie.</i>

1483
01:34:08,242 --> 01:34:11,075
Look, get out of here and take this flat-chested
goody-goody pain in the neck with you.

1484
01:34:11,178 --> 01:34:14,875
- Thank you.
- She is not a goody-goody.

1485
01:34:14,982 --> 01:34:17,542
<i>Oh, oh, before you go-</i>

1486
01:34:17,652 --> 01:34:19,847
Hey! Hey!

1487
01:34:19,954 --> 01:34:22,582
- Jesus! He's got a gun!
- What are you, crazy?

1488
01:34:22,690 --> 01:34:26,353
- I warn you, he's a Fourierist.
- It's only a joke, Rick.

1489
01:34:26,460 --> 01:34:29,657
<i>It's a toy or an antique or something.</i>

1490
01:34:29,764 --> 01:34:34,064
Well, then let the jerk
play his little game.

1491
01:34:46,380 --> 01:34:48,814
No, it's not that far.
It's, like, an hour.

1492
01:34:48,916 --> 01:34:51,043
Or- Or maybe two, probably.

1493
01:34:51,152 --> 01:34:53,552
Did anything happen?

1494
01:34:53,654 --> 01:34:55,554
Of course not.

1495
01:34:55,656 --> 01:34:58,750
Then you were never really interested
in Von Sloneker at all.

1496
01:35:00,861 --> 01:35:03,056
Well, then why did you
come out here?

1497
01:35:03,164 --> 01:35:05,132
To get a suntan.

1498
01:35:06,233 --> 01:35:09,225
The whole thing with the Rat Pack
was getting claustrophobic.

1499
01:35:09,336 --> 01:35:12,897
And Cynthia insisted I come.
She's terribly impressed with Rick.

1500
01:35:13,007 --> 01:35:16,443
It's not something Jane Austen
would have done.

1501
01:35:16,544 --> 01:35:19,342
No.

1502
01:35:19,447 --> 01:35:22,143
I suppose Europe is over there.

1503
01:35:22,249 --> 01:35:25,013
No, that'd be more Brazil.
Europe would be more that way.

1504
01:35:26,053 --> 01:35:29,181
Are you really going back next week?

1505
01:35:29,290 --> 01:35:31,918
I guess so.

1506
01:35:32,026 --> 01:35:34,995
What can you study in France
that you can't study here?

1507
01:35:38,065 --> 01:35:40,192
French.

1508
01:35:40,301 --> 01:35:43,634
Actually, I was thinking of coming back
when the semester ends.

1509
01:35:43,738 --> 01:35:47,936
I was thinking of going over, though not
necessarily to Grenoble, but to France or Italy.

1510
01:35:48,042 --> 01:35:49,942
Though my resources are limited.

1511
01:35:50,044 --> 01:35:53,673
There are some awfully cheap
airfares these days.

1512
01:35:53,781 --> 01:35:56,511
It would seem a shame
not to take advantage of them.

1513
01:35:56,617 --> 01:35:58,744
That's the way I feel.

1514
01:36:01,922 --> 01:36:04,550
Do you really think
I'm flat-chested?

1515
01:36:04,658 --> 01:36:07,354
Well, I never thought about it.
Well, I shouldn't say that.

1516
01:36:07,461 --> 01:36:11,192
The thing is, you look really great,
and that's what's important.

1517
01:36:11,298 --> 01:36:13,391
You don't wanna overdo it.

